  "lessons": [
    {
      "key": "Welcome to CSA",
      "name": "Lesson 1: Welcome to CSA",
      "absolute_position": 1,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**What does software engineering mean to me?**\n\nBelieving in one's own software engineering identity develops confidence and perseverance. In this lesson, students are introduced to key characteristics and skills of software engineers and explore common perceptions. Students realize that they have many of the same characteristics and skills as software engineers and discover their software engineering identity.",
        "preparation": "* Gather sticky notes (at least 20 for each student)\n* Print copies of the Software Engineering Skills handout (one half sheet for each student)\n* Preview the *Change the Face of Computer Science* and *Software Engineering: Skills and Characteristics* videos",
        "student_overview": "**What does software engineering mean to me?**\n\nBelieving in one's own software engineering identity develops confidence and perseverance. In this lesson, you are introduced to key characteristics and skills of software engineers and explore common perceptions. You have many of the same characteristics and skills as software engineers, which you realize as you discover your software engineering identity."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Welcome to CSA",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-18",
        "script.name": "csa1-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "lesson-25",
      "name": "Lesson 2: Introduction to Algorithms",
      "absolute_position": 2,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "In this lesson, students are introduced to the world of algorithms. They begin with a quick warm up activity exploring algorithms that they live out regularly in their lives. Then, they invent a new game, \"Enhanced Tic-Tac-Toe,\" wherein they have the option to write or diagram algorithms in order to develop unique, creative rules for this classic game. By making their own rules, students are able to recognize that an algorithm is a set of step-by-step instructions that accomplish a task. When students try the rules from another group, but with a twist, they grasp the importance of sequencing in designing an algorithm.",
        "preparation": "- Print copies of the Introduction to Algorithms activity guide (one per pair of students)",
        "student_overview": "In this lesson, you enter the world of algorithms. Starting with a quick warm up, you explore some of the \"daily algorithms\" you engage in regularly. Then, you have the chance to reimagine Tic-Tac-Toe by creating new rules for a 5x5 version of this classic game. Finally, you try the rules from another group, but with a special twist, in order to understand the importance of sequencing when designing an algorithm. "
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "lesson-25",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-18",
        "script.name": "csa1-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Java Lab",
      "name": "Lesson 3: Java Lab",
      "absolute_position": 3,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**What are some of the primary components of a Java program?**\n\nStudents are introduced to the Java Lab programming environment and its features. Students encounter their first Java program and explore the structure of a Java source code file. While investigating a simple program, students discover key components of a Java source code file, including the class header, the `main` method, syntax, and comments. Students then use their new knowledge of Java syntax to find and fix syntax errors.",
        "preparation": "* Print copies of the Investigate: Working with Java Files handout (one for each pair of students)",
        "student_overview": "**What are some of the primary components of a Java program?**\n\nIn this lesson, you are introduced to the Java Lab programming environment and its features. You encounter your first Java program and explore the structure of a Java source code file. While investigating a simple program, you discover key components of a Java source code file, including the class header, the `main` method, syntax, and comments. You then use your new knowledge of Java syntax to find and fix syntax errors."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Java Lab",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-18",
        "script.name": "csa1-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Classes and Objects",
      "name": "Lesson 4: Classes and Objects",
      "absolute_position": 4,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**What is object-oriented programming?**\n\nStudents are introduced to The Neighborhood and learn about the organization of the grid, potential obstacles, and some of the classes that make up The Neighborhood. Students begin to develop an understanding of classes and objects in Java and identify the components and relationship between these concepts. Students then explore the `Painter` class to identify the attributes and behavior that a `Painter` object has and can do and consider how they might use a `Painter` object in The Neighborhood.",
        "preparation": "* Preview the *Object-Oriented Programming* video\n* Print copies of The Painter handout (one for each student)",
        "student_overview": "**What is object-oriented programming?**\n\nIn this lesson, you are introduced to The Neighborhood and learn about the organization of the grid, potential obstacles, and some of the classes that make up The Neighborhood. You begin to develop an understanding of classes and objects in Java and identify the components and relationship between these concepts. You then explore the `Painter` class to identify the attributes and behavior that a `Painter` object has and can do and consider how they might use a `Painter` object in The Neighborhood."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Classes and Objects",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-18",
        "script.name": "csa1-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Instantiating Objects",
      "name": "Lesson 5: Instantiating Objects",
      "absolute_position": 5,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How do I create objects from a class?**\n\nStudents explored the fundamentals of object-oriented programming and the `Painter` class and identified its attributes and behaviors. In this lesson, students learn how to create objects from a class using the `new` keyword and by calling a constructor. Students discover that they can create multiple objects from a class and practice creating `Painter` objects to complete small programs in The Neighborhood.",
        "preparation": "* Preview the *Creating Objects* video",
        "student_overview": "**How do I create objects from a class?**\n\nYou explored the fundamentals of object-oriented programming and the `Painter` class and identified its attributes and behaviors. In this lesson, you learn how to create objects from a class using the `new` keyword and by calling a constructor. You discover that you can create multiple objects from a class and practice creating `Painter` objects to complete small programs in The Neighborhood."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Instantiating Objects",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-18",
        "script.name": "csa1-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Methods",
      "name": "Lesson 6: Methods",
      "absolute_position": 6,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How do I give instructions to an object in Java?**\n\nStudents have seen examples of programs where a `Painter` object is moving and painting in The Neighborhood. In this lesson, students explore the `move()` and `turnLeft()` methods in the `Painter` class and learn the syntax for calling methods in Java. Students then practice calling methods to navigate in The Neighborhood.",
        "preparation": "* Preview the *Calling Methods* video",
        "student_overview": "**How do I give instructions to an object in Java?**\n\nYou have seen examples of programs where a `Painter` object is moving and painting in The Neighborhood. In this lesson, you explore the `move()` and `turnLeft()` methods in the `Painter` class and learn the syntax for calling methods in Java. You then practice calling methods to navigate in The Neighborhood."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Methods",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-18",
        "script.name": "csa1-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Methods with Parameters",
      "name": "Lesson 7: Methods with Parameters",
      "absolute_position": 7,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How can I give a specific value for a method to use?**\n\nIn this lesson, students expand on what they have learned about methods to explore how method parameters and arguments are used to provide additional information for methods to perform their intended task, such as the `paint()` method in the `Painter` class. While learning about arguments, students are introduced to string literals and how to use these to specify paint colors. Students then practice calling methods with and without arguments to navigate and paint in The Neighborhood.",
        "student_overview": "**How can I give a specific value for a method to use?**\n\nIn this lesson, you expand on what you have learned about methods to explore how method parameters and arguments are used to provide additional information for methods to perform their intended task, such as the `paint()` method in the `Painter` class. While learning about arguments, you are introduced to string literals and how to use these to specify paint colors. You then practice calling methods with and without arguments to navigate and paint in The Neighborhood."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Methods with Parameters",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-18",
        "script.name": "csa1-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Inheritance",
      "name": "Lesson 8: Inheritance",
      "absolute_position": 8,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**Why would I use inheritance?**\n\nStudents have used the `Painter` class to navigate and paint in The Neighborhood and likely have noticed that the `Painter` class does not have a method to turn right. In this lesson, students learn about inheritance and the need to create superclasses and subclasses to represent similar objects that have shared attributes and behaviors. Students explore different use cases for inheritance and create a `PainterPlus` class as a subclass of the `Painter` class. Students realize that while the `PainterPlus` class has access to the methods in the `Painter` class, they can add new methods to expand its capabilities.",
        "preparation": "* Preview the *Inheritance* video",
        "student_overview": "**Why would I use inheritance?**\n\nThe `Painter` class has several methods for navigating and painting The Neighborhood, but it also has limitations. In this lesson, you learn about inheritance and the need to create superclasses and subclasses to represent similar objects that have shared attributes and behaviors. You explore different use cases for inheritance and create a `PainterPlus` class as a subclass of the `Painter` class. With your `PainterPlus` class, you have access to the methods in the `Painter` class and can add new methods to expand its capabilities."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Inheritance",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-18",
        "script.name": "csa1-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Writing Methods",
      "name": "Lesson 9: Writing Methods",
      "absolute_position": 9,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How do I write methods for the behaviors I want an object to have?**\n\nStudents have used the methods in the `Painter` class to navigate and paint in The Neighborhood and identified the limitations of the methods available in the `Painter` class. In this lesson, students learn to write and use methods in the `PainterPlus` class to expand its functionality. Students learn that a method with a `void` return type does not return a value and identify methods in the `Painter` class that have a `void` return type. The functionality of inheritance is emphasized when students discover that methods written in the `PainterPlus` class cannot be used by a `Painter` object. Students explore how to write methods with and without parameters then practice writing methods in their `PainterPlus` class.",
        "preparation": "* Preview the *Writing a Method* video",
        "student_overview": "**How do I write methods for the behaviors I want an object to have?**\n\nYou have used the methods in the `Painter` class to navigate and paint in The Neighborhood and identified the limitations of the methods available in the `Painter` class. In this lesson, you learn how to write and use methods in the `PainterPlus` class to expand its functionality. You learn that a method with a `void` return type does not return a value and identify methods in the `Painter` class that have a `void` return type. You strengthen your understanding of how inheritance works when you discover that methods written in the `PainterPlus` class cannot be used by a `Painter` object. You explore how to write methods with and without parameters then practice writing methods in your `PainterPlus` class."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Writing Methods",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-18",
        "script.name": "csa1-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "lesson-27",
      "name": "Lesson 10: Programming Style and Feedback",
      "absolute_position": 10,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How do software engineers use feedback from peers?**\n\nIn this lesson, students learn about the importance of good programming style and identify guidelines and best practices for formatting their code. Students explore processes and tools used by software engineers to manage projects, including documentation and commits. They learn about using multi-line comments in addition to single-line comments to annotate code, identify preconditions and postconditions, and explain the purpose and functionality of programs. Students also learn to use the Backpack in Java Lab to save classes they develop for use in future projects. To encourage and support collaboration and peer feedback on their work, students learn how to conduct a code review and best practices for giving and receiving feedback on code.",
        "preparation": "- Create code review groups as indicated on the Code Reviews for Teachers resource\n- Print copies of the How to Conduct a Code Review resource (one for each student)\n- Preview the *Software Engineering: Code Reviews* video",
        "student_overview": "**How do software engineers use feedback from peers?**\n\nIn this lesson, you learn about the importance of good programming style and identify guidelines and best practices for formatting your code. You explore processes and tools used by software engineers to manage projects, including documentation and commits. You learn about using multi-line comments in addition to single-line comments to annotate code, identify preconditions and postconditions, and explain the purpose and functionality of programs. You also learn to use the Backpack in Java Lab to save classes you develop for use in future projects. To encourage and support collaboration and peer feedback on your work, you learn how to conduct a code review and best practices for giving and receiving feedback on code."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "lesson-27",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-18",
        "script.name": "csa1-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Debugging Strategies",
      "name": "Lesson 11: Debugging Strategies",
      "absolute_position": 11,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How can I use the problem solving process to debug a program?**\n\nIn an introductory computer science course such as Computer Science Discoveries (CSD) or Computer Science Principles (CSP), students learned about bugs and debugging strategies. Students recall what they remember about debugging and consider how they have used the problem solving process to develop solutions to learn how to debug Java programs. Students explore variables, printing, and methods in the `Painter` class to obtain information about a `Painter` object and learn how to apply the problem solving process to find errors in a program and develop and test potential solutions. Students then practice using these strategies and the problem solving process to debug a program in The Neighborhood.",
        "preparation": "* Print copies of the Investigate: Debugging in The Neighborhood handout (one for each pair of students)\n* Preview the *Printing in Java* video",
        "student_overview": "**How can I use the problem solving process to debug a program?**\n\nYou have likely learned about bugs and debugging strategies in a previous computer science course. In this lesson, you recall what you remember about debugging and consider how you have used the problem solving process to develop solutions to learn how to debug Java programs. You explore variables, printing, and methods in the `Painter` class to obtain information about a `Painter` object and learn how to apply the problem solving process to find errors in a program and develop and test potential solutions. You then practice using these strategies and the problem solving process to debug a program in The Neighborhood."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Debugging Strategies",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-18",
        "script.name": "csa1-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Lesson 8: No-Argument Constructors",
      "name": "Lesson 12: No-Argument Constructors",
      "absolute_position": 12,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How does a constructor assign values to instance variables?**\n\nStudents have used constructors to create a variety of objects, including `Painter` objects. Students build on their knowledge of instance variables to explore how to assign values to the instance variables when an object is created. Students recall that the constructor they have used in the `Painter` class instantiates a `Painter` object with the same values every time, and they consider the decisions a software engineer needs to make to decide what default values should be assigned to instance variables. Students practice writing no-argument constructors and continue developing the `Dessert` class for the Joyful Pastries food truck.",
        "preparation": "* Preview the *Constructors* video",
        "student_overview": "**How does a constructor assign values to instance variables?**\n\nYou have used constructors to create a variety of objects, including `Painter` objects. In this lesson, you build on your knowledge of instance variables to explore how to assign values to the instance variables when an object is created. You recall that the constructor you have used in the `Painter` class instantiates a `Painter` object with the same values every time, and you consider the decisions a software engineer needs to make to decide what default values should be assigned to instance variables. You practice writing no-argument constructors and continue developing the `Dessert` class for the Joyful Pastries food truck."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Lesson 8: No-Argument Constructors",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-18",
        "script.name": "csa1-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Parameterized Constructors",
      "name": "Lesson 13: Parameterized Constructors",
      "absolute_position": 13,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 13,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How can I create objects with specific values for its instance variables?**\n\nStudents have learned how to write no-argument constructors to assign default values to instance variables and use these to instantiate objects. In this lesson, students consider the limitations of no-argument constructors and learn about using parameterized constructors to assign specific values to the instance variables. Students explore the components of a parameterized constructor and its functionality, then practice writing parameterized constructors in a class.",
        "preparation": "* Preview the *Overloaded Constructors* video",
        "student_overview": "**How can I create objects with specific values for its instance variables?**\n\nYou have learned how to write no-argument constructors to assign default values to instance variables and use these to instantiate objects. In this lesson, you consider the limitations of no-argument constructors and learn about using parameterized constructors to assign specific values to the instance variables. You explore the components of a parameterized constructor and its functionality, then practice writing parameterized constructors in a class."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Parameterized Constructors",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-18",
        "script.name": "csa1-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "User Input",
      "name": "Lesson 14: User Input",
      "absolute_position": 14,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 14,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How do I get input from the user?**\n\nIn this lesson, students learn how to collect input from users using the `Scanner` class. The lesson focuses on building programs that interact with users by asking for and processing input. Through guided notes, videos, and hands-on coding activities, students explore how to create and use `Scanner` objects and how to access documentation to learn more about available methods.",
        "preparation": "- Preview the *Creating Scanner Objects* and *Scanner Class Methods* videos",
        "student_overview": "**How do I get input from the user?**\n\nToday you learn how to make your programs interactive by asking the user for input. You use a tool in Java called the `Scanner` class to read information typed by the user. You practice writing code that takes this input and uses it in a program. You also learn how to look up more information about what the `Scanner` class can do and how to fix common mistakes in your code."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "User Input",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-18",
        "script.name": "csa1-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Constructors and Inheritance",
      "name": "Lesson 15: Constructors and Inheritance",
      "absolute_position": 15,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 15,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How can I assign values to the instance variables declared in a superclass from a subclass constructor?**\n\nStudents have learned how to write no-argument and parameterized constructors and used the `this` keyword to refer to the current object. In this lesson, students revisit inheritance and explore how to assign values to the instance variables declared in a superclass from a subclass constructor. Students learn how to use the `super` keyword to call the superclass constructor from a subclass and are introduced to the `Object` class. Students then practice writing no-argument and parameterized constructors in a subclass before applying these concepts to the `Dessert` subclasses they previously created.",
        "student_overview": "**How can I assign values to the instance variables declared in a superclass from a subclass constructor?**\n\nYou have learned how to write no-argument and parameterized constructors and use the `this` keyword to refer to the current object. In this lesson, you revisit inheritance and explore how to assign values to the instance variables declared in a superclass from a subclass constructor. You learn how to use the `super` keyword to call the superclass constructor from a subclass and are introduced to the `Object` class. You then practice writing no-argument and parameterized constructors in a subclass before applying these concepts to the `Dessert` subclass you previously created."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Constructors and Inheritance",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-18",
        "script.name": "csa1-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Variables",
      "name": "Lesson 16: Variables",
      "absolute_position": 16,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 16,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How are the types of variables in Java similar and different?**\n\nIn this lesson, students revisit variables and data types and learn the difference between primitive and reference types. Students investigate variables of type `int`, `double`, `boolean`, and `String` and explore using the assignment operator to initialize or change the value stored in a variable. Students then practice tracing code segments to identify the current values stored in variables.",
        "preparation": "* Preview the *Creating Variables* video\n* Print copies of the Investigate: Variables handout (one for each student)",
        "student_overview": "**How are the types of variables in Java similar and different?**\n\nIn this lesson, you revisit variables and data types and learn the difference between primitive and reference types. You investigate variables of type `int`, `double`, `boolean`, and `String` and explore using the assignment operator to initialize or change the value stored in a variable. You then practice tracing code segments to identify the current values stored in variables."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Variables",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-18",
        "script.name": "csa1-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Operators and Expressions",
      "name": "Lesson 17: Operators and Expressions",
      "absolute_position": 17,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 17,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How can I use variables and operators to perform calculations?**\n\nStudents have learned how to use variables to store primitive values and object references. In this lesson, students explore writing and evaluating expressions using arithmetic operators and compound assignment operators. Students discover how the data type impacts the way an expression is evaluated and the result of dividing an `int` or a `double` value by zero. They also learn about using compound assignment operators and explore the mod ( `%` ) operator.",
        "student_overview": "**How can I use variables and operators to perform calculations?**\n\nYou have learned how to use variables to store primitive values and object references. In this lesson, you explore writing and evaluating expressions using arithmetic operators and compound assignment operators. You discover how the data type impacts the way an expression is evaluated and the result of dividing an `int` or a `double` value by zero. You also learn about using compound assignment operators and explore the mod ( `%` ) operator."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Operators and Expressions",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-18",
        "script.name": "csa1-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "lesson-26",
      "name": "Lesson 18: Casting and Range of Variables",
      "absolute_position": 18,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 18,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**What happens if a value in your program falls beyond the maximum or minimum range of values?**\n\nIn this lesson, students explore what it means for computers to have a specified amount of memory for data storage, and how different data types have storage allotted. They discover the minimum and maximum values for integers and how exceeding these limits causes overflow or underflow errors. They investigate strategies for avoiding overflow errors, and adapt those strategies to avoid roundoff errors. Students then practice writing methods to check for and avoid overflow errors. \n",
        "student_overview": "**What happens if a value in your program falls beyond the maximum or minimum range of values?**\n\nIn this lesson, you will dive into how computers store data and the limits each data type has. You'll uncover the boundaries for integers and what happens if you go beyond them, leading to overflow or underflow errors. We'll explore ways to prevent these errors and also learn about roundoff errors. Finally, you'll get hands-on experience writing methods to detect and steer clear of overflow errors."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "lesson-26",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-18",
        "script.name": "csa1-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Printing Objects",
      "name": "Lesson 19: Printing Objects",
      "absolute_position": 19,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 19,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How can I easily display information about an object?**\n\nStudents have learned to use accessor methods to obtain information about the state of an object. In this lesson, students explore how to print an object reference and the `toString()` method to easily obtain information about an object. Students revisit the `Object` class and learn how to override its `toString()` method and practice writing a `toString()` method in a class using escape sequences to format output. Students then write a `toString()` method in the `Dessert` class and subclass.",
        "preparation": "* Preview *The toString() Method* video",
        "student_overview": "**How can I easily display information about an object?**\n\nYou have learned to use accessor methods to obtain information about the state of an object. In this lesson, you explore how to print an object reference and the `toString()` method to easily obtain information about an object. You revisit the `Object` class and learn how to override its `toString()` method and practice writing a `toString()` method in a class using escape sequences to format output. You then write a `toString()` method in the `Dessert` class and subclass."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Printing Objects",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-18",
        "script.name": "csa1-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Lesson 1: The Theater",
      "name": "Lesson 20: The Theater",
      "absolute_position": 20,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 20,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**What can I make with The Theater?**\n\nIn this unit, students explore data visualizations and consider how they can create their own visuals to tell a story about a dataset. Students start by exploring The Theater through an existing program and reading documentation to identify the available classes and methods they can use to create drawings, show images, and play sounds. They then practice using these methods to create simple drawings and visuals and consider how they can use The Theater to create animations and visualizations of the dataset they used for their Data for Social Good Project.",
        "preparation": "* Preview the *Welcome to The Theater* video\n* Print copies of the Investigating The Theater handout (one for each pair of students)",
        "student_overview": "**What can I make with The Theater?**\n\nIn this unit, you explore data visualizations and consider how you can create your own visuals to tell a story about a dataset. You start by exploring The Theater through an existing program and reading documentation to identify the available classes and methods you can use to create drawings, show images, and play sounds. You then practice using these methods to create simple drawings and visuals and consider how you can use The Theater to create animations and visualizations of the dataset you used for your Data for Social Good Project."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Lesson 1: The Theater",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-18",
        "script.name": "csa1-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "The Math Class",
      "name": "Lesson 21: The Math Class",
      "absolute_position": 21,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 21,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**What can I do with the `Math` class?**\n\nStudents have used classes like `Scanner` and `Object` from the Java API as well as classes from The Neighborhood and The Theater. In this lesson, students learn about the `Math` class and how the `static` keyword can be used with the `final` keyword to create constants. They explore the documentation for the `Math` class to identify its methods and learn about their functionalities. Students then practice creating and using constants and calling methods in the `Math` class.",
        "preparation": "* Preview the *Constants* video\n* Print copies of The Math Class handout (one for each student)\n* Print copies of the Math Class Graphic Organizer handout (one for each student)",
        "student_overview": "**What can I do with the `Math` class?**\n\nYou have used classes like `Scanner` and `Object` from the Java API as well as classes from The Neighborhood and The Theater. In this lesson, you learn about the `Math` class and how the `static` keyword can be used with the `final` keyword to create constants. You explore the documentation for the `Math` class to identify its methods and learn about their functionalities. You then practice creating and using constants and calling methods in the `Math` class."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "The Math Class",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-18",
        "script.name": "csa1-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Random",
      "name": "Lesson 22: Random",
      "absolute_position": 22,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 22,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How can I generate and use random numbers?**\n\nStudents learned about the `Math` class in the previous lesson and explored using some of its methods to perform calculations. In this lesson, students learn about the functionality of `Math.random()` and discover its benefits and limitations. Students consider how they can use `Math.random()` with casting operators to generate random numbers within a specific range and consider how random is used in programs they use every day. They then practice generating and using random numbers within specified ranges and retrieving random elements from a 1D array.",
        "preparation": "* Preview the *Random Numbers* video",
        "student_overview": "**How can I generate and use random numbers?**\n\nYou learned about the `Math` class in the previous lesson and explored using some of its methods to perform calculations. In this lesson, you learn about the functionality of `Math.random()` and discover its benefits and limitations. You consider how you can use `Math.random()` with casting operators to generate random numbers within a specific range and consider how random is used in programs you use every day. You then practice generating and using random numbers within specified ranges and retrieving random elements from a 1D array."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Random",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-18",
        "script.name": "csa1-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Substrings",
      "name": "Lesson 23: Substrings",
      "absolute_position": 23,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 23,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How can I analyze parts of a `String` object?**\n\nIn this lesson, students revisit the `String` class and learn how to use the `substring()` method. They discover that `String` objects are immutable and are not modified when calling methods in the `String` class. Students also explore how the `substring()` method can be combined with other methods in the `String` class to find the location of a specific character or substring within a `String` and compare substrings for equality. They then practice using the `substring()` method to retrieve a substring of a `String` object and to find and replace specific characters.",
        "student_overview": "**How can I analyze parts of a `String` object?**\n\nIn this lesson, you revisit the `String` class and learn how to use the `substring()` method. You discover that `String` objects are immutable and are not modified when calling methods in the `String` class. You also explore how the `substring()` method can be combined with other methods in the `String` class to find the location of a specific character or substring within a `String` and compare substrings for equality. You then practice using the `substring()` method to retrieve a substring of a `String` object and to find and replace specific characters."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Substrings",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-18",
        "script.name": "csa1-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Comparing Strings",
      "name": "Lesson 24: Comparing Strings",
      "absolute_position": 24,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 24,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How can I determine if a list of `String` objects are in alphabetical order?**\n\nStudents have previously learned how to use several of the methods in the String class. In this lesson, students explore the `compareTo()` method and discover how this method can be used to check if a list of `String` objects is in alphabetical order. They then practice using the `compareTo()` method to evaluate `String` objects and using the methods in the `String` class to implement algorithms.",
        "student_overview": "**How can I determine if a list of `String` objects are in alphabetical order?**\n\nYou have previously learned how to use several of the methods in the `String` class. In this lesson, you explore the `compareTo()` method and discover how this method can be used to check if a list of `String` objects is in alphabetical order. You then practice using the `compareTo()` method to evaluate `String` objects and using the methods in the `String` class to implement algorithms."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Comparing Strings",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-18",
        "script.name": "csa1-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Overloaded Methods",
      "name": "Lesson 25: Overloaded Methods",
      "absolute_position": 25,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 25,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How can overloading a method be useful in my programs?**\n\nStudents previously learned about overloading when writing multiple constructors in a class. In this lesson, students revisit overloaded constructors and learn how overloading can be applied to methods. They explore how overloaded methods work and consider scenarios where overloaded methods would be useful. Students then practice writing and calling overloaded methods and revisit their Need to Knows to determine what they have learned that will be useful for their project and what they still need to learn.",
        "student_overview": "**How can overloading a method be useful in my programs?**\n\nYou previously learned about overloading when writing multiple constructors in a class. In this lesson, you revisit overloaded constructors and learn how overloading can be applied to methods. You explore how overloaded methods work and consider scenarios where overloaded methods would be useful. You then practice writing and calling overloaded methods and revisit your Need to Knows to determine what you have learned that will be useful for your project and what you still need to learn."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Overloaded Methods",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-18",
        "script.name": "csa1-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Asphalt Art Project",
      "name": "Project 1a: Asphalt Art Project",
      "absolute_position": 26,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 26,
      "properties": {
        "assessment": true,
        "overview": "​​**What do I want to represent using programming and art?**\n\nFor this project, students use the skills they have developed to create asphalt art in The Neighborhood. Students choose a theme or concept for their asphalt art that represents something they are interested in or meaningful to them. After brainstorming and planning, students develop their programs to create their designs.",
        "preparation": "* Review project setup, requirements, and rubric\n* Print copies of the Asphalt Art Project Planning Guide handout (one for each student)\n* Create code review groups if you are not reusing the same groups\n* Gather several sticky notes for each student",
        "student_overview": "**What do I want to represent using programming and art?**\n\nFor this project, you use the skills you have developed to create asphalt art in The Neighborhood. You choose a theme or concept for your asphalt art that represents something you are interested in or meaningful to you. After brainstorming and planning, you develop your program to create your design."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Asphalt Art Project",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-2",
        "script.name": "csa1-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Asphalt Art Project [1-Day Version]",
      "name": "Project 1b: Asphalt Art Project [1-Day Version]",
      "absolute_position": 27,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 27,
      "properties": {
        "assessment": true,
        "overview": "​​**What do I want to represent using programming and art?**\n\nFor this project, students use the skills they have developed to create asphalt art in The Neighborhood. Students choose a theme or concept for their asphalt art that represents something they are interested in or meaningful to them. After brainstorming and planning, students develop their programs to create their designs.",
        "preparation": "* Review project requirements and rubric\n* Print copies of the Asphalt Art Project Planning Guide handout (one for each student)"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Asphalt Art Project [1-Day Version]",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-2",
        "script.name": "csa1-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "SpiralPainter FRQ",
      "name": "FRQ 1: SpiralPainter FRQ",
      "absolute_position": 28,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 28,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How will I use what I know about classes, objects, and methods to answer a Free Response Question?**\n\nStudents are introduced to AP CSA Free Response Questions (FRQs) and practice decomposition and problem-solving skills to develop solutions to a mock FRQ. Students use annotation strategies to identify the key components of the problem and validate their solutions using Scoring Guidelines.",
        "preparation": "* Print the SpiralPainter FRQ Stations resource\n* Cut out the manipulatives in the SpiralPainter FRQ Stations resource *or* have students make a copy of the SpiralPainter FRQ Digital Manipulatives\n* Create stations around the classroom as indicated on the SpiralPainter FRQ Stations resource\n* (Optional) Gather a blue, orange, and pink colored pencil or marker for each student",
        "student_overview": "**How will I use what I know about classes, objects, and methods to answer a Free Response Question?**\n\nYou are asked to develop solutions to Free Response Questions (FRQs) on the AP CSA Exam. You learn about the structure of an FRQ and practice decomposition and problem-solving skills to develop solutions to a mock FRQ. You use annotation strategies to identify the key components of the problem and validate your solutions using Scoring Guidelines."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "SpiralPainter FRQ",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "csa1-alt-2025"
      }
    },
