  ],
  "activity_sections": [
    {
      "key": "040568c5-d177-463c-912f-ca675a63207e",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Welcome to Computer Science A! We will learn a lot about computer science and programming this year. To get started, let's hear about how you can change the face of computer science.",
        "name": "Changing the Face of CS",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "040568c5-d177-463c-912f-ca675a63207e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "8cef66a5-6dee-4f53-a53e-bd33e1212e5c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ad2694e9-940d-4d7d-b2c4-2e40081a710f",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Display: Show the video – *Change the Face of Computer Science*.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Prompt students to share their reactions, thoughts, and feelings about the video. Ask students to suggest areas that they think are impacted by or involve computer science and to share ideas about problems that can be solved using computer science.\n\nThis can also be an opportunity for students to share concerns they might have about taking the class. Share your own concerns you had when learning Java to demonstrate sharing vulnerabilities to help students feel comfortable sharing their own. This can also help you learn about your students and their needs so you can determine how best to support them."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ad2694e9-940d-4d7d-b2c4-2e40081a710f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "8cef66a5-6dee-4f53-a53e-bd33e1212e5c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f27af774-3288-4e77-a3d7-c2df188eb9da",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Design Thinking: Group Brainstorm"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f27af774-3288-4e77-a3d7-c2df188eb9da",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4bf2229c-279a-474d-81d2-a78f6ad2f528"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2b8ae68a-f19d-4c51-9936-85b1b40541dd",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "You won't just explore software engineering in this class – you will be software engineers.\n\nWe will use a common design thinking activity known as group brainstorming to gather some ideas about software engineering.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2b8ae68a-f19d-4c51-9936-85b1b40541dd",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4bf2229c-279a-474d-81d2-a78f6ad2f528"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3af6fb03-4f00-4fdb-915e-84f4dddcc686",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student at least 20 sticky notes.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to write a word or phrase on a sticky note in response to the prompt.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Encourage students to write down as many as they can think of. There are no wrong answers! As students write words or phrases, circulate the room to support their beliefs by:\n* Agreeing with the statements they have written.\n* Affirming the value of a particular idea.\n* Making connections between statements on different students' desks to help them confirm that they are part of a community of people who are not so different from themselves."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3af6fb03-4f00-4fdb-915e-84f4dddcc686",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4bf2229c-279a-474d-81d2-a78f6ad2f528"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "782eb02e-ac9c-4125-9941-31793f055ac1",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "782eb02e-ac9c-4125-9941-31793f055ac1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4bf2229c-279a-474d-81d2-a78f6ad2f528"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "bde0b0d8-0aa4-4363-a887-3329b22a1980",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "As you wrote down ideas, you were probably more confident about some than others. To help create a collective understanding of how we view software engineering right now, we will create groups of sticky notes. Your goal is to identify themes and similarities that you see when looking at all of your sticky notes together. It’s up to you to decide how to group them!",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "bde0b0d8-0aa4-4363-a887-3329b22a1980",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4bf2229c-279a-474d-81d2-a78f6ad2f528"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c1bb0d9a-c314-4a46-8a76-9fd46daa64cf",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Group:** Place students in groups of three or four.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to share the ideas they wrote, group sticky notes based on similar themes, and display their notes on designated wall space.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If you do not have wall space that you can designate for students to post their notes, you can have students display their notes on a desk or table instead."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c1bb0d9a-c314-4a46-8a76-9fd46daa64cf",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4bf2229c-279a-474d-81d2-a78f6ad2f528"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e62b80ae-7d88-44d1-bb10-4f2bf998b435",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e62b80ae-7d88-44d1-bb10-4f2bf998b435",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4bf2229c-279a-474d-81d2-a78f6ad2f528"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1ac39b01-e722-4785-9e4b-c3124c796ad0",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Let's take a look at the ideas and themes your classmates identified through a Gallery Walk.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Design Thinking: Gallery Walk and Discussion",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1ac39b01-e722-4785-9e4b-c3124c796ad0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4bf2229c-279a-474d-81d2-a78f6ad2f528"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b7535ee5-70c4-4cbb-adfb-0a6d9a1c4818",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to participate in a Gallery Walk to view other ideas and groupings. Students write what they notice and wonder on a new sticky note.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "A Gallery Walk allows students to view multiple ideas, perspectives, and solutions. Students walk around the classroom to view each other's work, allowing each student to share ideas with the class and giving a voice to students who may be hesitant to share verbally."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b7535ee5-70c4-4cbb-adfb-0a6d9a1c4818",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4bf2229c-279a-474d-81d2-a78f6ad2f528"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c47627ad-af89-4583-bdf9-c605d84db270",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c47627ad-af89-4583-bdf9-c605d84db270",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4bf2229c-279a-474d-81d2-a78f6ad2f528"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "51e8ff06-0360-4048-a40d-72ec9e4e8429",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What do you notice?*\n* *What do you wonder?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students identify key ideas and common themes they noticed in other groups. Students may wonder why differences exist across groups and the cause or basis of these ideas.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *Where do we get our perceptions from? Why?*\n* *What message do we get from these?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students share how popular culture and media influence their perceptions about software engineers. Students share examples of how movies, TV shows, and social media portray software engineers.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Students might feel hesitant to share their thoughts. You could choose to modify this discussion by:\n* Having small groups write down their thoughts on a student whiteboard.\n* Having students write a response on a scratch sheet of paper, then throw it across the room. Students pick up a piece of paper close to them and read it to themselves. You can choose to call on students to share the response they picked up.\n\nCollect the sticky notes. The ideas students shared will be revisited in Lesson 15. Choose common words and phrases to enter on the indicated slide in Lesson 15."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "51e8ff06-0360-4048-a40d-72ec9e4e8429",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4bf2229c-279a-474d-81d2-a78f6ad2f528"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f9ff6591-2409-4d4d-9e29-cfc11118ae1c",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "description": "It's helpful to hear from an expert about something we may not know much about. Let's hear from some software engineers about their work and the skills they use.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Skills of a Software Engineer",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f9ff6591-2409-4d4d-9e29-cfc11118ae1c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4bf2229c-279a-474d-81d2-a78f6ad2f528"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9be5749b-f714-447f-b164-2c4c8746e14b",
      "position": 13,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define the term ***software engineer***.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Display: Show the video – *Software Engineering: Skills and Characteristics*.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Videos are used throughout the curriculum to spark discussions, supplement key concepts with additional explanations and examples, and expose students to the various roles and backgrounds of individuals in computer science.\n\nWhile interacting with the video, turn on closed captioning so students can also read along as they watch.\n\nTo encourage active engagement and reflection, use one or more of the strategies discussed in the [**Guide to Curriculum Videos**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1FqIUpJg6MrgdtbFGLobSojOz0u1m5Jge1nMAjUqI5ZM/edit?usp=sharing)."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9be5749b-f714-447f-b164-2c4c8746e14b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4bf2229c-279a-474d-81d2-a78f6ad2f528"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "03432346-4b49-43b8-b4c0-02314cadf9ec",
      "position": 14,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "03432346-4b49-43b8-b4c0-02314cadf9ec",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4bf2229c-279a-474d-81d2-a78f6ad2f528"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "176a4090-06eb-47f0-9525-ce918af7a3cc",
      "position": 15,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What skills and characteristics do you think are important for software engineering?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students recall skills and characteristics discussed in the video, such as problem-solving, collaboration, creativity, and curiosity. Students share ideas about why these characteristics and skills are important for software engineering.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *When have you shown these characteristics inside or outside of school? How?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students realize they have already displayed many of the characteristics and skills of a software engineer in school and at home."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "176a4090-06eb-47f0-9525-ce918af7a3cc",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4bf2229c-279a-474d-81d2-a78f6ad2f528"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4bfd5cca-fec8-488f-a9ec-8f798d3bc409",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "These characteristics and skills are the most important parts of being a software engineer. You may not realize it yet, but you already have the mindset of a software engineer.",
        "name": "Developing a Software Engineering Identity",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4bfd5cca-fec8-488f-a9ec-8f798d3bc409",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1d9c197a-4120-4f52-bd3b-8acda33bc157"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3d958d1d-b32b-4b1a-bd0c-5d97c2cfc310",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student a copy of the Software Engineering Characteristics handout.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to choose one software engineering characteristic or skill that they feel is their strongest and one that they feel they have the most room for growth.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the concepts covered in this lesson.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Question of the Day.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Key Vocabulary"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3d958d1d-b32b-4b1a-bd0c-5d97c2cfc310",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1d9c197a-4120-4f52-bd3b-8acda33bc157"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4aa0afeb-a941-4f92-b3f6-4644ff8d55aa",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Think about a task you do each day that has clear steps. With your partner, create a list of these steps, and ensure that your list is clear enough for a machine to follow.*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** By recognizing and sharing the step-by-step processes in their daily routines, students are able to identify familiar tasks, break them down into clear and ordered steps, and express those steps clearly. This activity should lay the foundation for the introduction to algorithms in this lesson.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Emphasize the importance of diverse perspectives while students collaborate with their partners. Encourage students to share their ideas with the whole class by underscoring that the goal is not to find one correct set of steps, but to consider multiple different approaches. "
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4aa0afeb-a941-4f92-b3f6-4644ff8d55aa",
        "lesson_activity.key": "721900a6-dee5-4d25-93de-ed47c3f94dc5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "476e505e-8e6d-4844-bf85-287f31d94bae",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "476e505e-8e6d-4844-bf85-287f31d94bae",
        "lesson_activity.key": "721900a6-dee5-4d25-93de-ed47c3f94dc5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "52b4b200-b728-42bc-80a9-b4758cef4284",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "When we break down daily tasks into a step-by-step process, we are creating an algorithm. We can describe algorithms in writing like this, or by using diagrams. Notice that the order of the steps matters in order for the algorithms to be successful. ",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "52b4b200-b728-42bc-80a9-b4758cef4284",
        "lesson_activity.key": "721900a6-dee5-4d25-93de-ed47c3f94dc5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "89b72710-f6a9-41dd-8cbf-28c33f5a261a",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *algorithm* and introduce the components of an algorithm.",
        "duration": "20",
        "name": "Rules for Enhanced Tic-Tac-Toe"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "89b72710-f6a9-41dd-8cbf-28c33f5a261a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "0b1f079f-eec3-4681-be85-231c432d735d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e51c7e31-e7ef-4f05-a5c6-68c18f866a8d",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We now know that an algorithm is built of a sequence of steps that should be done in a certain order. Now let’s use algorithms to add a couple of twists to a classic game, Tic-Tac-Toe.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e51c7e31-e7ef-4f05-a5c6-68c18f866a8d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "0b1f079f-eec3-4681-be85-231c432d735d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "22dd156b-e39c-4a60-9207-8cd484f007b5",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Group:** Group students into pairs. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each pair of students a copy of the Introduction to Algorithms activity guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Students work with their partners to create an enhanced version of Tic-Tac-Toe by adding additional challenges. ",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Students may need encouragement in order to try creating new rules. Encourage students to experiment and to take risks as they try out new rules. Emphasize the importance of testing different possibilities, and emphasize that it is okay for a rule to be awkward or imperfect. "
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "22dd156b-e39c-4a60-9207-8cd484f007b5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "0b1f079f-eec3-4681-be85-231c432d735d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4dfce0ee-0cd3-4a2f-9e36-6812d0df8e6d",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** As students finish playing one or two rounds with their partner and their new rules, encourage them to reflect on what they’ve done so far.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Testing and Reflecting",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Retrieve-Pair-Share strategy to facilitate this discussion by directing students to write down their thoughts and ideas first, then pair up students to compare their answers and expand their notes. This allows time for individual processing and idea generation before sharing thoughts with others. Ask students to share the ideas they discussed with their partners as a class. "
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4dfce0ee-0cd3-4a2f-9e36-6812d0df8e6d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "0b1f079f-eec3-4681-be85-231c432d735d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9d5644ec-22e1-4d18-b86e-607f04716014",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9d5644ec-22e1-4d18-b86e-607f04716014",
        "lesson_activity.key": "0b1f079f-eec3-4681-be85-231c432d735d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d026800e-4c43-42f9-9c75-27615e4ca49d",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "You've made a couple of new rules yourself, and now it is time to put them to the test, and to test out a game from another group. But there’s a twist! As you try out another group's rules, try doing them in a different order than what is suggested. Does this make a difference for the game play?",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d026800e-4c43-42f9-9c75-27615e4ca49d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "0b1f079f-eec3-4681-be85-231c432d735d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "73e5b982-4337-4f20-86d5-23057e233931",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Group:** Combine pairs into groups of four. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Students review the rules from another group's version of \"Enhanced Tic-Tac-Toe.\" They play a couple of games of this version, but with the steps in a different order than specified. ",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Teachers should circulate and encourage students to actively engage with the algorithms created by other groups. Ensure students are still following the rules, but that they are modifying the order of those rules. The teacher can encourage meta-cognition here by asking guiding questions about the importance of sequencing, and the need to clearly describe each step. "
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "73e5b982-4337-4f20-86d5-23057e233931",
        "lesson_activity.key": "0b1f079f-eec3-4681-be85-231c432d735d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a426ec78-a568-4ef2-86e5-f8d92070e8c5",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a426ec78-a568-4ef2-86e5-f8d92070e8c5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "0b1f079f-eec3-4681-be85-231c432d735d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "38a8cee1-950c-42d7-b864-d43a88757c74",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** As groups finish playing one or two rounds, encourage them to reflect on what they’ve done so far.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Retrieve-Pair-Share strategy to facilitate this discussion by directing students to write down their thoughts and ideas first, then pair up students to compare their answers and expand their notes. This allows time for individual processing and idea generation before sharing thoughts with others. Ask students to share the ideas they discussed with their partners as a class. "
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "38a8cee1-950c-42d7-b864-d43a88757c74",
        "lesson_activity.key": "0b1f079f-eec3-4681-be85-231c432d735d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5dc79f6a-0b4c-4dc3-a105-0b38e2ffbb7f",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5dc79f6a-0b4c-4dc3-a105-0b38e2ffbb7f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "0b1f079f-eec3-4681-be85-231c432d735d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f8c5415a-6b80-4bd2-ad13-891b4f790ca1",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Algorithms are the building blocks of the programs we build in computer science. The rules that you wrote today for this new version of tic-tac-toe are a great example of an algorithm. In order for your algorithm to be effective, it must be clearly written or diagramed, and the steps must be followed in the order you specified. ",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f8c5415a-6b80-4bd2-ad13-891b4f790ca1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "0b1f079f-eec3-4681-be85-231c432d735d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d6c60b8b-c468-487a-99b5-e8cc1965da8c",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Do This: Students use the \"Questions to Consider\" to answer the final reflection questions in the activity guide.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If time permits, students can share their answers with a neighbor or with the whole class. Students can be encouraged to celebrate the challenges and confusions they may have encountered as opportunities for growth. "
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d6c60b8b-c468-487a-99b5-e8cc1965da8c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "59b8fdd6-37d0-4ed0-b49e-c7eb2aab95f3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "00d6ae0e-1d00-478a-bca0-45b56784bae9",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "00d6ae0e-1d00-478a-bca0-45b56784bae9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "59b8fdd6-37d0-4ed0-b49e-c7eb2aab95f3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5daa6fd2-84bf-4531-b38e-b5befb7426ae",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the concepts covered in this lesson.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Question of the Day.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Key Vocabulary"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5daa6fd2-84bf-4531-b38e-b5befb7426ae",
        "lesson_activity.key": "59b8fdd6-37d0-4ed0-b49e-c7eb2aab95f3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e36052f9-e2eb-4276-955d-329331549fcd",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Computing and programming used to have different meanings than they have today. Before electronic computers were invented, a computer was a person who performs mathematical calculations. From the late nineteenth century onwards, people had to perform long, tedious calculations. It was common for women to do this job.",
        "name": "Human Computers",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e36052f9-e2eb-4276-955d-329331549fcd",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f0756430-e07b-487d-b330-bc2d891aa07b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "08d78e16-9764-4d45-8e0f-bbfedd9a2dfa",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Share the story of the ENIAC project and the female programmers that operated it.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to write down ideas and thoughts in response to the prompt on a sticky note or scrap piece of paper.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Throughout the curriculum, students are exposed to examples of computer science in different industries or problems that could potentially be solved using computer science. These are intended to contribute to the development of their identities as software engineers and challenge their perceptions about who software engineers are and what they do. As you learn about your students and their personal interests, you can change these scenarios to show examples of computer science connected to their personal interests to make these more meaningful for your classroom."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "08d78e16-9764-4d45-8e0f-bbfedd9a2dfa",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f0756430-e07b-487d-b330-bc2d891aa07b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6b75cbbe-9672-41c5-a48a-4f422683fb14",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6b75cbbe-9672-41c5-a48a-4f422683fb14",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f0756430-e07b-487d-b330-bc2d891aa07b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c248aae9-de38-44db-8415-1bfb8c425ccb",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Play the music clip to cue the Give One, Get One activity and direct students to participate in a Give One, Get One.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Using music to cue transitions helps create routines in the classroom. When students hear cues, they know it is time to transition to a specific activity. Emphasize to students what the music clip means, and be consistent with the use of the music clip to cue the activity.\n\nClick the blue play icon on the slide to play the music cue.\n\nGive One, Get One encourages students to seek and share ideas and information. Students circulate the classroom and pair up with a partner when prompted by the teacher. Each student \"gives\" or shares one of their ideas as the other student \"gets\" or listens and writes it down. The teacher then prompts students to find new partners and repeat the process."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c248aae9-de38-44db-8415-1bfb8c425ccb",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f0756430-e07b-487d-b330-bc2d891aa07b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "24ef3b1e-ff33-492e-be6a-7815b7f1a36f",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "24ef3b1e-ff33-492e-be6a-7815b7f1a36f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f0756430-e07b-487d-b330-bc2d891aa07b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f956b210-66e4-4920-ba3a-a688317dd931",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What did you learn from each other?*\n* *How did these ideas and thoughts contribute to your identity as a software engineer?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students share the ideas they gathered and identify patterns or common views. Students identify characteristics of a software engineer that programmers on the ENIAC had and how they share or demonstrate these same characteristics in their personal lives."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f956b210-66e4-4920-ba3a-a688317dd931",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f0756430-e07b-487d-b330-bc2d891aa07b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e4fbc27c-2846-4d7f-b2aa-499fb7ce48f7",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Introduction"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e4fbc27c-2846-4d7f-b2aa-499fb7ce48f7",
        "lesson_activity.key": "8656fb92-516a-491e-a4c8-88f724beeb3c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "617bedf3-04a7-4bb8-a529-28fe55c8f463",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Software engineers use various tools to write and test programs. In this class, we will use Java Lab as our programming tool to write our code. We will explore Java Lab's features and learn how Java files are structured.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "617bedf3-04a7-4bb8-a529-28fe55c8f463",
        "lesson_activity.key": "8656fb92-516a-491e-a4c8-88f724beeb3c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0692e415-e18e-4caa-843d-dfa9be04c93d",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce Java Lab.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Point out the **Run** and **Settings** button on the screen. The **Run** button allows students to run the program to see the output of the program, and the **Settings** button allows students to switch between light and dark mode and change the text size. Students will explore the **Test** button during the Investigate and Modify activity."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0692e415-e18e-4caa-843d-dfa9be04c93d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "8656fb92-516a-491e-a4c8-88f724beeb3c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8173046b-ef73-47a0-89f6-3314e0c2c19b",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8173046b-ef73-47a0-89f6-3314e0c2c19b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "8656fb92-516a-491e-a4c8-88f724beeb3c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f0bc0387-1648-4d6e-afc6-bb0ab498b451",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 1 on Code Studio to predict the program's outcome, then run the program to compare their predictions to the actual outcome.",
        "progression_name": "Predict and Run: A Java Program"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f0bc0387-1648-4d6e-afc6-bb0ab498b451",
        "lesson_activity.key": "8656fb92-516a-491e-a4c8-88f724beeb3c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2cd79d57-3493-4e26-99ff-9d2bf572ae75",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What did you notice about the code in this program?*\n* *What do you wonder about the code in this program?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students notice a `Painter` that moves and turns left in the grid displayed in Java Lab. They identify that the `Painter` performs these actions from commands that are given to the `Painter`, and the program executes these commands in the order given. Students might wonder where the `Painter` comes from or about other commands they can give the `Painter`."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2cd79d57-3493-4e26-99ff-9d2bf572ae75",
        "lesson_activity.key": "8656fb92-516a-491e-a4c8-88f724beeb3c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4880f6fc-788b-4ea5-a230-c01844fe4419",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***source code***.\n\n**Group:** Place students in pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each pair a copy of the Investigate: Working with Java Files handout.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 2 on Code Studio. Students investigate the program with their partner and complete the Investigate: Working with Java Files handout.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Java Source Code",
        "progression_name": "Investigate and Modify: Working with Java Files",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Encourage students to focus on understanding how Java code is written rather than the functionality of the programs. Emphasize that they will learn about how the code works throughout the unit."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4880f6fc-788b-4ea5-a230-c01844fe4419",
        "lesson_activity.key": "8656fb92-516a-491e-a4c8-88f724beeb3c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e4ce0264-7ad5-4001-a082-3f2b6c96e2ac",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e4ce0264-7ad5-4001-a082-3f2b6c96e2ac",
        "lesson_activity.key": "8656fb92-516a-491e-a4c8-88f724beeb3c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "150806d4-cbc9-414f-a4a4-21349fabc776",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students share what they discovered from the modifications they made to the code and their responses on the Investigate: Working with Java Files handout."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "150806d4-cbc9-414f-a4a4-21349fabc776",
        "lesson_activity.key": "8656fb92-516a-491e-a4c8-88f724beeb3c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "84a5abd0-333b-4351-ae5e-3db5996df4d3",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "A Java program is made up of one or more Java source code files. Each source code file gives instructions to Java to tell it what we want it to do and the order we want the tasks to execute. When we write Java source code files, we have to be sure to follow certain rules so our program runs as expected.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "84a5abd0-333b-4351-ae5e-3db5996df4d3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "8656fb92-516a-491e-a4c8-88f724beeb3c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2af53b97-2152-44c8-934f-ef51f39d6460",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain the Java syntax rules and define ***syntax***.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain how Java source code files are named.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***class header***.\n\n**Do This:** Explain the syntax and purpose of the `main` method:\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> The purpose of the `main` method\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Java looks for the `main` method to determine where to start running the program\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> The `String[] args` in the `main` method\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***comment***."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2af53b97-2152-44c8-934f-ef51f39d6460",
        "lesson_activity.key": "8656fb92-516a-491e-a4c8-88f724beeb3c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "11ac2f98-089a-4841-81e9-26c1ea887d22",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "description": "When we are writing code, we can sometimes encounter errors that prevent our programs from running. This is a normal part of the programming process. In fact, software engineers spend a lot of time finding and fixing errors in their own programs!",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Finding and Fixing Syntax Errors",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "11ac2f98-089a-4841-81e9-26c1ea887d22",
        "lesson_activity.key": "8656fb92-516a-491e-a4c8-88f724beeb3c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9dde95af-f351-459a-b9f4-1e1c2deca3ff",
      "position": 13,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What do you think it means for a program to have a syntax error?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students make predictions about the definition of syntax error based on what they know about syntax. Students may share examples that might cause a syntax error, such as forgetting a semicolon or writing the `main` method incorrectly.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Retrieve-Pair-Share strategy to facilitate this discussion by directing students to write down their thoughts and ideas on the Unit 1 Guide first, then pair up students to compare their answers and expand their notes. This allows time for individual processing and idea generation before sharing thoughts with others. Ask students to share the ideas they discussed with their partners as a class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9dde95af-f351-459a-b9f4-1e1c2deca3ff",
        "lesson_activity.key": "8656fb92-516a-491e-a4c8-88f724beeb3c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0bd36e6f-870c-4667-adef-cddf5e5612d8",
      "position": 14,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0bd36e6f-870c-4667-adef-cddf5e5612d8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "8656fb92-516a-491e-a4c8-88f724beeb3c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "db3840eb-be6e-4b49-98de-c20e02104960",
      "position": 15,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***syntax error***.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 3 on Code Studio to complete Levels 3 and 4. Students complete Check for Understanding on Level 3, then continue to Level 4 to complete a choice level to find and fix the syntax errors in the program.",
        "progression_name": "Practice: Syntax Errors",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Choice levels allow students to choose a problem to complete based on the level of complexity or personal interest. Some choice levels are differentiated by complexity, while others are similar levels of complexity but differentiated by topic. Students only need to complete one level but can complete multiple for additional practice if they choose."
          },
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Check for Understanding and practice levels can be used as formative assessments to gauge understanding of vocabulary presented in the lesson and Java syntax. "
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "db3840eb-be6e-4b49-98de-c20e02104960",
        "lesson_activity.key": "8656fb92-516a-491e-a4c8-88f724beeb3c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "33e19f0b-8007-4462-9ca8-834846eac8e9",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We have learned a lot about Java Lab and how Java source code files are written! Let's recap what we have learned and think about where we go from here.",
        "name": "Three W's",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "33e19f0b-8007-4462-9ca8-834846eac8e9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "abb05f49-6146-40b6-a18b-96d714157ff1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8f0b0136-c031-4e54-972b-50188ccbb13a",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What did we learn today?*\n* *So what?*\n* *Now what?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students highlight the concepts and vocabulary they learned in this lesson, such as syntax, class headers, and the `main` method. Students also identify the features in Java Lab that allow them to write, run, and test their programs. They should realize that the knowledge they gained in this lesson provides them a foundation to build on to develop more complex programs and make predictions about what they might learn next.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the concepts covered in this lesson.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Question of the Day.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Key Vocabulary"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8f0b0136-c031-4e54-972b-50188ccbb13a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "abb05f49-6146-40b6-a18b-96d714157ff1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "23189db1-58cc-48af-bb13-8b9f6dd58e77",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "---"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "23189db1-58cc-48af-bb13-8b9f6dd58e77",
        "lesson_activity.key": "abb05f49-6146-40b6-a18b-96d714157ff1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "fa72bade-11fe-4f4f-bf9e-2a47647b712c",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "*Check For Understanding Question(s) and solutions can be found in each lesson on Code Studio. These questions can be used for an exit ticket.*",
        "name": "Assessment: Check for Understanding",
        "progression_name": "Check for Understanding"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "fa72bade-11fe-4f4f-bf9e-2a47647b712c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "abb05f49-6146-40b6-a18b-96d714157ff1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d1cdfd52-a125-4b07-875d-fe43f5d20f29",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to draw a house, then have students share their drawing with a neighbor.",
        "name": "Defining a Blueprint",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Emphasize to students that their drawings should be quick sketches that focus on the core elements of a house. There is space on the Unit 1 Guide for students to create their drawings."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d1cdfd52-a125-4b07-875d-fe43f5d20f29",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e8ed91f2-db1b-4af3-a938-40ec66f19cfd"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a94c7933-fcf9-4ab3-a4c5-4978c972b901",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a94c7933-fcf9-4ab3-a4c5-4978c972b901",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e8ed91f2-db1b-4af3-a938-40ec66f19cfd"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "dbcbdc72-bd7f-46d3-a724-cd88575202a2",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What elements does everyone's house have in common?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students identify common elements in the drawings, such as having a door, windows, or a roof.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What information might we include if we were to create a blueprint for what all houses should have?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students suggest that a blueprint for all houses might specify a front door, the number of windows, the shape of the building, or the shape of the roof."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "dbcbdc72-bd7f-46d3-a724-cd88575202a2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e8ed91f2-db1b-4af3-a938-40ec66f19cfd"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "89567515-bef2-4983-b9e8-457065c887a4",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Introduction"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "89567515-bef2-4983-b9e8-457065c887a4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b3321267-e0cb-44bd-83d6-466a3f526a99"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6eda446b-a153-409b-b717-e50eb8d2925b",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Software engineers have to make decisions similar to the ones you just made to decide what elements are important to represent in a program. When you decide what elements all houses should have, you establish a blueprint for building houses that someone can use to ensure every house they build has these elements. Today we're going to learn how this process works in Java.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6eda446b-a153-409b-b717-e50eb8d2925b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b3321267-e0cb-44bd-83d6-466a3f526a99"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6bb49662-ee31-413a-848a-e3e353e91c3e",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Show the video – *Object-Oriented Programming*.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Videos are used throughout the curriculum to spark discussions, supplement key concepts with additional explanations and examples, and expose students to the various roles and backgrounds of individuals in computer science.\n\nWhile interacting with the video, turn on closed captioning so students can also read along as they watch.\n\nTo encourage active engagement and reflection, use one or more of the strategies discussed in the [**Guide to Curriculum Videos**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1FqIUpJg6MrgdtbFGLobSojOz0u1m5Jge1nMAjUqI5ZM/edit?usp=sharing)."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6bb49662-ee31-413a-848a-e3e353e91c3e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b3321267-e0cb-44bd-83d6-466a3f526a99"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1a3a9bbb-34b4-4e76-a0d0-b067317c3926",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1a3a9bbb-34b4-4e76-a0d0-b067317c3926",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b3321267-e0cb-44bd-83d6-466a3f526a99"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f3a4e85d-7938-4b77-83e1-2257081e74cd",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that Java is an object-oriented programming language and define ***object-oriented programming***."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f3a4e85d-7938-4b77-83e1-2257081e74cd",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b3321267-e0cb-44bd-83d6-466a3f526a99"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "544072c6-b0c4-4fd0-b501-a014437190ef",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 1 on Code Studio to predict the program's outcome, then run the program to compare their predictions to the actual outcome.",
        "progression_name": "Predict and Run: Classes and Objects"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "544072c6-b0c4-4fd0-b501-a014437190ef",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b3321267-e0cb-44bd-83d6-466a3f526a99"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e7fa1975-92a5-4348-bf90-7cd3b164e67e",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What did you notice about the code in this program?*\n* *What do you wonder about the code in this program?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students notice two files in the program and that one has the `main` method while the other does not. Students notice that the class with the `main` method refers to the name of the other class and then performs an action. Students may wonder about the purpose of the file that does not have a `main` method or about the syntax and functionality of the code.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to define ***class*** and ***object***.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Remind students of the houses they drew at the beginning of the lesson. Identify the blueprint for building a house as an example of a class, and a physical house that is built according to the blueprint as an example of an object."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e7fa1975-92a5-4348-bf90-7cd3b164e67e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b3321267-e0cb-44bd-83d6-466a3f526a99"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c55919ae-cd30-4bed-ac92-8e91da892738",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c55919ae-cd30-4bed-ac92-8e91da892738",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b3321267-e0cb-44bd-83d6-466a3f526a99"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "718a9969-60f0-4da6-a22e-0b06809fb9a2",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain the meaning of an instance of a class.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Do you think there is a limit to how many objects you can create from a class? Why or why not?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students share their thoughts about whether or not they think there is a limit and justify their reasoning. Students should realize that they can create multiple objects from a class because the class is a blueprint for how objects should be created."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "718a9969-60f0-4da6-a22e-0b06809fb9a2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b3321267-e0cb-44bd-83d6-466a3f526a99"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6b10790e-be24-4585-843b-90528ff259e9",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "When we identified elements that all houses should have, we were choosing things that all houses should have. This blueprint would allow someone to create house objects that each have their own versions of these elements.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "The Painter Class",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6b10790e-be24-4585-843b-90528ff259e9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b3321267-e0cb-44bd-83d6-466a3f526a99"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2d8ca6e5-b64f-4b46-8a10-fd9ce0d7064b",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce The Neighborhood.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Ask students to identify the similarities between the grid in The Neighborhood and grids they may have seen in other classes, such as their math classes. Be sure to point out that the x and y coordinates start at 0 from the top-left corner and that the size of the grid is one more than the last position."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2d8ca6e5-b64f-4b46-8a10-fd9ce0d7064b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b3321267-e0cb-44bd-83d6-466a3f526a99"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "62bfc516-6169-48ab-8082-02d109903a15",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "62bfc516-6169-48ab-8082-02d109903a15",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b3321267-e0cb-44bd-83d6-466a3f526a99"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8049dcc7-0d85-4d4d-940f-f35ac61ccdef",
      "position": 13,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Consider your own neighborhood and the things that are in it. If you were to represent your neighborhood as a collection of classes, what classes would your neighborhood consist of?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students make suggestions about how their neighborhood might be represented in a program, such as creating classes to represent a house, a family, a park, and a street light.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Hold That Thought strategy to allow students to write down their thoughts on paper first. Emphasize that they do not need to write complete sentences – they can write a few words, bullet points, draw a quick sketch, or anything else that will help them gather and recall their thoughts when it is time to share with the class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8049dcc7-0d85-4d4d-940f-f35ac61ccdef",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b3321267-e0cb-44bd-83d6-466a3f526a99"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "681dafd8-0f22-41a4-a195-aaf2183a99ad",
      "position": 14,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "681dafd8-0f22-41a4-a195-aaf2183a99ad",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b3321267-e0cb-44bd-83d6-466a3f526a99"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "054325b1-7107-405f-849f-b58aad4991fe",
      "position": 15,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What else could you represent in a Java program as a class?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students share examples of real or imagined objects they could represent as a class, such as a book, a sport, or player in a game.\n\n**Group:** Place students in pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student a copy of the The Painter handout.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 2 on Code Studio to investigate the program with their partners and complete The Painter handout.",
        "progression_name": "Investigate and Modify: The Painter Class",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "The code for the `Painter` class on this level is not the complete functioning code for the `Painter` class. This version of the `Painter` class is simplified to help students focus on the key components to explore while completing The Painter handout. Emphasize to students to focus on identifying the attributes and behaviors and reassure them that they will be learning about the syntax and functionality of these components."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "054325b1-7107-405f-849f-b58aad4991fe",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b3321267-e0cb-44bd-83d6-466a3f526a99"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "62e96e27-21df-4719-be2b-bd3ddc1b15bf",
      "position": 16,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "62e96e27-21df-4719-be2b-bd3ddc1b15bf",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b3321267-e0cb-44bd-83d6-466a3f526a99"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "cc7e2519-ec69-4cf3-99e8-2a1bcd67e5c1",
      "position": 17,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to introduce UML diagrams.\n\n**Do This:** Explain the components of the `Painter` class:\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Introduce the `Painter` class\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Define ***attribute***\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Define ***behavior***",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Point out that a `Painter` object has attributes to represent its x and y location on the grid, the direction it is facing, and how much paint it has. Note that a `Painter` object has behaviors that allow it to move, turn left, take paint from a paint bucket, and paint a space in The Neighborhood."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "cc7e2519-ec69-4cf3-99e8-2a1bcd67e5c1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b3321267-e0cb-44bd-83d6-466a3f526a99"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6f81408c-e0b3-4e2f-8ed1-42c9bc1d2047",
      "position": 18,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6f81408c-e0b3-4e2f-8ed1-42c9bc1d2047",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b3321267-e0cb-44bd-83d6-466a3f526a99"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "af6669b1-b080-4d96-b7d0-255d9eecc3d4",
      "position": 19,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Now that you’ve explored the Painter class and its methods, what are some creative or problem-solving tasks you could use a Painter object to accomplish in The Neighborhood?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students brainstorm creative or problem-solving tasks that a Painter object could complete in The Neighborhood, such as navigating a maze or painting a mural. Students reference methods they explored in the Painter class and consider how those methods could be combined to achieve more complex outcomes."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "af6669b1-b080-4d96-b7d0-255d9eecc3d4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b3321267-e0cb-44bd-83d6-466a3f526a99"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "603ffce6-dc47-4a27-a530-ce3bdc0d37bd",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Classes and objects are key components of a Java program. With classes, we can represent all types of real or imagined objects with attributes and behaviors that are important to our programs. Let's take a moment to review what we have learned so far.",
        "name": "Glows, Grows, Want-to-Knows",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "603ffce6-dc47-4a27-a530-ce3bdc0d37bd",
        "lesson_activity.key": "288b666d-cc18-4097-9145-73d3a49c3493"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f6fb0f22-b36b-4008-aaca-bb7d58dc7c8a",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n- *What is something you understand well about classes, objects, attributes, or behaviors?*\n- *What is something you’re still unsure about or want more practice with?*\n- *What is a question you still have about how classes and objects work in Java?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students reflect on their understanding of classes and objects by identifying concepts they feel confident about and areas where they need more practice. Students also surface lingering questions or misconceptions, supporting peer-to-peer clarification and reinforcing foundational object-oriented programming concepts.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the concepts covered in this lesson.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Question of the Day.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Key Vocabulary"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f6fb0f22-b36b-4008-aaca-bb7d58dc7c8a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "288b666d-cc18-4097-9145-73d3a49c3493"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a8149e71-a0fc-4154-bace-5a697ec02f78",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "---"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a8149e71-a0fc-4154-bace-5a697ec02f78",
        "lesson_activity.key": "288b666d-cc18-4097-9145-73d3a49c3493"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "89d1521b-68dd-4007-8caa-3c410c08bfa0",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "*Check For Understanding Question(s) and solutions can be found in each lesson on Code Studio. These questions can be used for an exit ticket.*",
        "name": "Assessment: Check for Understanding",
        "progression_name": "Check for Understanding"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "89d1521b-68dd-4007-8caa-3c410c08bfa0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "288b666d-cc18-4097-9145-73d3a49c3493"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "03cb8110-0f83-46da-8166-3029137c9ffe",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "In the previous lesson, we learned that Java is an object-oriented programming language. Classes and objects are key components of a Java program and make up many of the programs and apps we use every day.",
        "name": "Classes in Other Programs",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "03cb8110-0f83-46da-8166-3029137c9ffe",
        "lesson_activity.key": "14c804cd-59a1-466b-854b-4733daaa8be3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "cf56a07a-b9ca-4916-b5c3-62adf85c5a6a",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the discussion prompt. \n- Apps and programs we use every day are built using classes—for example, Instagram might include a User class, a Post class, or a Comment class.\n  - *What is an app you use often?*\n  - *What is one class that might be part of that app, and what could it do?*\n\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students share examples of programs and apps they use, such as a social media app. Students suggest classes that might make up those programs and apps, such as a `User` or `Post` class.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Retrieve-Pair-Share strategy to facilitate this discussion by directing students to write down their thoughts and ideas on the Unit 1 Guide first, then pair up students to compare their answers and expand their notes. This allows time for individual processing and idea generation before sharing thoughts with others. Ask students to share the ideas they discussed with their partners as a class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "cf56a07a-b9ca-4916-b5c3-62adf85c5a6a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "14c804cd-59a1-466b-854b-4733daaa8be3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4addf914-02ed-44e4-94f6-e45a9300fc66",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Instantiation"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4addf914-02ed-44e4-94f6-e45a9300fc66",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a1701697-502e-47e9-aba4-1170e02ca4dc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4b5f1973-b3ab-45a2-a26a-5d540f170db2",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "With the `Painter` class, or blueprint, we can create `Painter` objects. Since the `Painter` class is part of The Neighborhood, we don't have to tell Java what a `Painter` is every time we want to create a `Painter` object. Software engineers wrote the `Painter` class for us to use, so we don't have to know the details about how it was written to create `Painter` objects. This also means that we can trust that the `Painter` class works as the software engineers who wrote it intended.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4b5f1973-b3ab-45a2-a26a-5d540f170db2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a1701697-502e-47e9-aba4-1170e02ca4dc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8e98ab40-3242-41df-8e78-fdd6ab9650cc",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Show the video – *Creating Objects*.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Videos are used throughout the curriculum to spark discussions, supplement key concepts with additional explanations and examples, and expose students to the various roles and backgrounds of individuals in computer science.\n\nWhile interacting with the video, turn on closed captioning so students can also read along as they watch.\n\nTo encourage active engagement and reflection, use one or more of the strategies discussed in the [**Guide to Curriculum Videos**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1FqIUpJg6MrgdtbFGLobSojOz0u1m5Jge1nMAjUqI5ZM/edit?usp=sharing)."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8e98ab40-3242-41df-8e78-fdd6ab9650cc",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a1701697-502e-47e9-aba4-1170e02ca4dc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1abbaf0f-bb72-4e43-97ec-6c76183c018d",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1abbaf0f-bb72-4e43-97ec-6c76183c018d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a1701697-502e-47e9-aba4-1170e02ca4dc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9a080dda-f084-4a9a-98ba-84bbab0d71ff",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Do This:** Explain the syntax for creating an object:\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Specify the class, or type of object\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Give a name for the object\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> The `new` keyword\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Call the ***constructor*** to create the object",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Let students know that they will learn what those instructions look like and how to write their own in the next unit."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9a080dda-f084-4a9a-98ba-84bbab0d71ff",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a1701697-502e-47e9-aba4-1170e02ca4dc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "59793847-3aa9-45d2-9f5e-d373a82b3e43",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***instantiate***.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that creating an object is creating an instance of a class and that a program can have multiple instances of a class.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Recall the houses warmup activity from the previous lesson and the definition of a class. Guide students to make the connection between blueprints being used to build multiple houses, so classes can be used to create multiple objects."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "59793847-3aa9-45d2-9f5e-d373a82b3e43",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a1701697-502e-47e9-aba4-1170e02ca4dc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c8729c66-de60-46b8-9bf6-6d5046435d99",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c8729c66-de60-46b8-9bf6-6d5046435d99",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a1701697-502e-47e9-aba4-1170e02ca4dc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "518c4cfa-b135-452f-b9eb-4c236bfbf080",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 1 on Code Studio to instantiate the missing `Painter` object.",
        "progression_name": "Skill Building: Painter Objects",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "This Skill Building level can be used as a formative assessment to gauge understanding of the syntax for instantiating an object."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "518c4cfa-b135-452f-b9eb-4c236bfbf080",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a1701697-502e-47e9-aba4-1170e02ca4dc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "cc010558-85fb-4075-877e-6c40292e0848",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What do you notice about how a `Painter` object is instantiated? Where does it start? Does it always start at the same location?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students note that a `Painter` object always starts at (0, 0) facing east with 0 units of paint. Every `Painter` object they create starts the same way.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain the default values for a `Painter` object's attributes when a `Painter` object is instantiated.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Painter Objects",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Students will learn more about what it means to assign default values to attributes and the default values for different data types in the next unit."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "cc010558-85fb-4075-877e-6c40292e0848",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a1701697-502e-47e9-aba4-1170e02ca4dc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "17a7538a-c702-40c2-ad9b-3d833b9fb708",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "17a7538a-c702-40c2-ad9b-3d833b9fb708",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a1701697-502e-47e9-aba4-1170e02ca4dc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "effefff1-3852-4a83-b072-aed7d845e93e",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 2 on Code Studio to complete Levels 2, 3, and 4. Students complete a Check for Understanding on Level 2, then continue to Level 3 to instantiate the missing `Painter` object. On Level 4, students instantiate multiple `Painter` objects to complete the program.",
        "progression_name": "Practice: Painter Objects"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "effefff1-3852-4a83-b072-aed7d845e93e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a1701697-502e-47e9-aba4-1170e02ca4dc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8a90bdad-d6ae-4934-9c07-27b5038acf24",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We have learned a lot about object-oriented programming!",
        "name": "Closing the Loop",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8a90bdad-d6ae-4934-9c07-27b5038acf24",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c8979ad0-c4b5-4a99-8211-72dfd59342f5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "71da91c7-b6c8-4fb4-93d4-4ff9fc71b6d5",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What is the difference between a class and an object?*\n* *What’s something in today’s lesson that helped you understand how Java works a little better?*\n* *What were you confident about? What would you like to practice?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students explain the difference between a class and an object and connect the house example from the warm up activity. Students suggest examples of things they have encountered similar to a class and objects created from the class. Students share concepts from the lesson that they are confident about and concepts they might be confused about.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Closing the Loop helps students recap concepts and reflect on their learning process. This discussion is also an opportunity to normalize any confusion students are experiencing. Highlight that this is new information for most students and that there will be times when they feel lost or confused. Share your own experience learning Java for the first time. You can also ask students to share strategies for when they are confused, such as consulting additional resources."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "71da91c7-b6c8-4fb4-93d4-4ff9fc71b6d5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c8979ad0-c4b5-4a99-8211-72dfd59342f5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "adfffe05-7dd4-469f-85a1-af6067d045bb",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "adfffe05-7dd4-469f-85a1-af6067d045bb",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c8979ad0-c4b5-4a99-8211-72dfd59342f5"
      }
    },
