    {
      "key": "40636a18-5b40-4da6-a1d0-128c2665ce64",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "*Check For Understanding Question(s) and solutions can be found in each lesson on Code Studio. These questions can be used for an exit ticket.*",
        "name": "Assessment: Check for Understanding",
        "progression_name": "Check for Understanding"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "40636a18-5b40-4da6-a1d0-128c2665ce64",
        "lesson_activity.key": "17a763a7-2288-4c1c-9bb1-c81efabf408a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "88c808fc-2390-42fc-9aba-1f0f47a1f467",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Besides defining classes and creating objects, software engineers write instructions to tell Java how to complete tasks. When we give instructions, we have to be as clear and concise as possible to ensure that Java completes the task the way we intend. We do this in our day-to-day lives as well.",
        "name": "Instructions with Inputs",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "88c808fc-2390-42fc-9aba-1f0f47a1f467",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d74d2655-e636-423a-b68b-0f0a0b98eb42"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "46414858-bbb4-4f84-8799-01823edf2abc",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Consider our delivery driver from the previous lesson. Before we could give our instructions for how to reach the destination, what information did we need to know first?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students share examples of information needed to perform the task, such as the location the delivery driver needed to reach or where the delivery driver started. Students may also suggest that they needed to know their current location as they were navigating to determine which direction to turn next.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Retrieve-Pair-Share strategy to facilitate this discussion by directing students to write down their thoughts and ideas on the Unit 1 Guide first, then pair up students to compare their answers and expand their notes. This allows time for individual processing and idea generation before sharing thoughts with others. Ask students to share the ideas they discussed with their partners as a class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "46414858-bbb4-4f84-8799-01823edf2abc",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d74d2655-e636-423a-b68b-0f0a0b98eb42"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8f003300-df39-4cbc-bd8d-f71b378bb09f",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Introduction"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8f003300-df39-4cbc-bd8d-f71b378bb09f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3c90d1f9-dee2-41e9-8ff4-8dd0960f0fc6"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "22a1e57c-7ae7-4572-9f29-ff73201b4d4b",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Our `Painter` objects can do more than just move and turn in The Neighborhood. We can also use our `Painter` objects to paint! Let's take a look at the `paint()` method in the `Painter` class and how we can use this to paint in The Neighborhood.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "22a1e57c-7ae7-4572-9f29-ff73201b4d4b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3c90d1f9-dee2-41e9-8ff4-8dd0960f0fc6"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "dc39578f-cc95-4e7b-85ed-0efdd2e46749",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 1 on Code Studio to predict the program's outcome, then run the program to compare their predictions to the actual outcome.",
        "progression_name": "Predict and Run: Painting"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "dc39578f-cc95-4e7b-85ed-0efdd2e46749",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3c90d1f9-dee2-41e9-8ff4-8dd0960f0fc6"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a3b246ab-4075-4b17-aba3-81d261a47fff",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What did you notice about the code in this program?*\n* *What do you wonder about the code in this program?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students notice the `paint()` method and that it is called with a color inside quotation marks. Students may wonder about the color options available for painting."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a3b246ab-4075-4b17-aba3-81d261a47fff",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3c90d1f9-dee2-41e9-8ff4-8dd0960f0fc6"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "91adfe9a-884f-4d6d-ab6e-696a441eded1",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Sometimes methods need additional information before they can perform their intended task. For example, if we want a calculator to add two numbers, we first have to provide the two numbers we want it to add before we can get the result. The `paint()` method in the `Painter` class is an example of this. Let's take a closer look at how we use this method.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Methods with Parameters",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "91adfe9a-884f-4d6d-ab6e-696a441eded1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3c90d1f9-dee2-41e9-8ff4-8dd0960f0fc6"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "cae6ca8f-90e7-4ecc-90ef-55b502e476a4",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 2 on Code Studio to complete Levels 2, 3, and 4. Students investigate the program by modifying the program as prompted and observing the results.",
        "progression_name": "Investigate and Modify: Painting"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "cae6ca8f-90e7-4ecc-90ef-55b502e476a4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3c90d1f9-dee2-41e9-8ff4-8dd0960f0fc6"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "da928d71-2bec-4a79-af03-ff472aa66090",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students share what they discovered from the modifications they made to the code.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the `paint()` method in the `Painter` class.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***parameter***.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to explain how the `paint()` method is called and define ***argument***.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***string literal***.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "The available colors students can use are listed in the documentation for the `Painter` class. Remind students about the colors they discovered when they explored the Documentation tab in Java Lab during the Investigate activity. Students can also pass a hex value for a color as a `String` to the call to the `paint()` method. For students that want to use custom colors, you can refer them to websites like [**HTML Colors Codes**](https://htmlcolorcodes.com/) to use the color picker and find the hex value of a color."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "da928d71-2bec-4a79-af03-ff472aa66090",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3c90d1f9-dee2-41e9-8ff4-8dd0960f0fc6"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1dfc6eec-04e8-495b-a206-b35286ef827d",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "With methods, we can give our objects instructions to perform tasks that we want them to do. Now that we have learned about some of the methods in the `Painter` class, let's practice calling methods to navigate and paint around The Neighborhood!",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Moving and Painting",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1dfc6eec-04e8-495b-a206-b35286ef827d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3c90d1f9-dee2-41e9-8ff4-8dd0960f0fc6"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "208786ae-81d3-43e0-a2ae-25777e1f5042",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 5 to complete Levels 5 and 6 on Code Studio. Students complete a Check for Understanding on Level 5, then continue to Level 6 to practice using some of the methods in the `Painter` class.",
        "progression_name": "Practice: Moving and Painting",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Check for Understanding and practice levels can be used as formative assessments to gauge understanding of vocabulary presented in the lesson and the syntax for calling methods with and without parameters."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "208786ae-81d3-43e0-a2ae-25777e1f5042",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3c90d1f9-dee2-41e9-8ff4-8dd0960f0fc6"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "976f2407-5c18-4bff-a125-71a12d42d129",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "You all have done a great job today using your knowledge of Java and the methods in the `Painter` class to solve problems in The Neighborhood! You used several software engineering characteristics today as you practiced being a problem solver, creator, collaborator, and learner to expand your skills.",
        "name": "Glows, Grows, Want-to-Knows",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "976f2407-5c18-4bff-a125-71a12d42d129",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a5321c4a-da6c-4bc6-a89d-85787bad4753"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "de1aa1a2-f016-436b-b486-ba7ef01b02a8",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What was awesome about writing your code?*\n* *What is one action you can take to improve your code?*\n* *What questions do you have about today?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students share aspects of their program they enjoyed or how they solved the problem and identify areas of improvement to strengthen their programming skills. Students also share any questions or misconceptions they may have.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Glows, Grows, Want-to-Knows is a strategy to help students identify their strengths and areas of improvement and share any questions or misconceptions."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "de1aa1a2-f016-436b-b486-ba7ef01b02a8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a5321c4a-da6c-4bc6-a89d-85787bad4753"
      }
    },
    {
