    {
      "key": "b8953961-d10d-4b32-a213-e1fae30ea053",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "You have learned a lot about object-oriented programming and software engineering already! Let's take a moment to reflect on and capture what we now know.",
        "name": "OOP Review",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b8953961-d10d-4b32-a213-e1fae30ea053",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9912d248-1918-48df-a953-0837935e33c2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "69fd0bde-29b1-4b72-8d1a-d4b01ed8292e",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to create a concept map in response to the prompt by brainstorming any concepts and ideas that come to mind.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "A concept map helps students illustrate their understanding of the relationships between the concepts they have learned so far. It usually consists of at least two concepts (nouns), a relationship (verb or short description), and an arrow connecting the concepts. This tool allows students to develop stronger connections with the topic and helps them identify what they know and where gaps might exist.\n\nThere is space on the guided notes for students to create their concept maps.\n\nYou can also revisit this throughout the remainder of the unit to have students continue adding to and revising their concept map."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "69fd0bde-29b1-4b72-8d1a-d4b01ed8292e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9912d248-1918-48df-a953-0837935e33c2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ea09a35d-efdc-4ec2-8ca6-e0da1a0cc501",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ea09a35d-efdc-4ec2-8ca6-e0da1a0cc501",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9912d248-1918-48df-a953-0837935e33c2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e27469b8-bc9f-4363-8f25-35ee7265cb58",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students review their brainstorm, identify the concepts that are central to the prompt, and draw arrows to connect the concepts.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to label the arrows with verbs or short descriptions to identify the relationships between the concepts.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students share their concept maps with a neighbor to compare concepts and relationships. Have students add to or revise their concept maps based on their discussions.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The concept map can be used as a formative assessment to gauge understanding of the concepts students have learned so far. This can help determine if any concepts need to be revisited or clarified as you begin the lesson."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e27469b8-bc9f-4363-8f25-35ee7265cb58",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9912d248-1918-48df-a953-0837935e33c2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "79cdfe28-7073-4647-ae37-54a588d07bbc",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Inheritance"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "79cdfe28-7073-4647-ae37-54a588d07bbc",
        "lesson_activity.key": "5802724c-42c0-4be7-8322-5185e1e19edb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7ac7ad98-43dd-4e7f-ad27-69acc66b75a5",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We have written algorithms using sequencing and iteration to have our `Painter` objects navigate and paint in The Neighborhood. While these algorithms have made it easier to give our `Painter` objects instructions, we are still limited to the methods in the `Painter` class.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7ac7ad98-43dd-4e7f-ad27-69acc66b75a5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "5802724c-42c0-4be7-8322-5185e1e19edb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c26524a5-8784-4a66-887f-4aa402f0d57f",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *If you could add a new method to the `Painter` class, what method would you want to add?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students suggest several methods based on their experience in The Neighborhood so far, such as a method to turn right or to take all paint from a paint bucket.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Prompt students to recall the algorithms they developed in the previous lesson. Ask students if any of those algorithms would be useful as a method and what they might name these methods."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c26524a5-8784-4a66-887f-4aa402f0d57f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "5802724c-42c0-4be7-8322-5185e1e19edb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f5cf5a7c-50d8-4ad0-8526-97a6edcd13b0",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f5cf5a7c-50d8-4ad0-8526-97a6edcd13b0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "5802724c-42c0-4be7-8322-5185e1e19edb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5f1afb4c-5eb7-42f0-8c9f-9a4ddef49bc6",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Group:** Place students in groups of four.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students participate in a Roundtable to brainstorm potential solutions to the scenario: *The software engineer knows that this `Instrument` class works to represent a guitar at a music store, but the owner wants to also sell pianos. How should the software engineer implement these changes? What if the music store owner later decides to also sell other instruments?*",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Each group should have a single sheet of paper. Each student in the group takes turns responding to the question or problem by stating their ideas out loud to the group as they write them on the paper. The paper is then passed around the group until time is called.\n\nLet students know that if their thoughts are at a standstill, they are allowed to say \"Pass\" and let the brainstorming continue to the next student."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5f1afb4c-5eb7-42f0-8c9f-9a4ddef49bc6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "5802724c-42c0-4be7-8322-5185e1e19edb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6af5bb5b-634d-442f-9870-ad2180f0c68c",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6af5bb5b-634d-442f-9870-ad2180f0c68c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "5802724c-42c0-4be7-8322-5185e1e19edb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "96bc915a-49c5-477f-852d-8ca24b0ddc49",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "When software engineers write code that they know works the way they intended, they want to make sure their code *stays working*. Oftentimes that means not letting other people change that code.\n\nBut there are times when we *do* need to change that code. Instead of making changes to code that we know works, we can extend our working code without making changes to it.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "96bc915a-49c5-477f-852d-8ca24b0ddc49",
        "lesson_activity.key": "5802724c-42c0-4be7-8322-5185e1e19edb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "48b572af-d67e-46c0-b014-908a94150da4",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Show the video – *Inheritance*.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Videos are used throughout the curriculum to spark discussions, supplement key concepts with additional explanations and examples, and expose students to the various roles and backgrounds of individuals in computer science.\n\nWhile interacting with the video, turn on closed captioning so students can also read along as they watch.\n\nTo encourage active engagement and reflection, use one or more of the strategies discussed in the [**Guide to Curriculum Videos**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1FqIUpJg6MrgdtbFGLobSojOz0u1m5Jge1nMAjUqI5ZM/edit?usp=sharing)."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "48b572af-d67e-46c0-b014-908a94150da4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "5802724c-42c0-4be7-8322-5185e1e19edb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d3f1f5cb-3aeb-4359-b23d-4f70f71ec948",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d3f1f5cb-3aeb-4359-b23d-4f70f71ec948",
        "lesson_activity.key": "5802724c-42c0-4be7-8322-5185e1e19edb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0b954ade-d239-4124-8e0e-a1dba70da283",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***inheritance*** and explain that the `Dog` and `Cat` class inherit from the `Pet` class.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***superclass***.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***subclass***.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain the is-a relationship.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What are some scenarios where you would want to use inheritance?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students suggest using inheritance when they want to extend an existing class that either cannot be changed or that would not be ideal to change because of the risks to its functionality. Students should also suggest using inheritance to represent relationships between different types of objects that share similar attributes and behaviors.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Remind students of the `Instrument` class scenario. Ask students how inheritance would be beneficial for that scenario and the classes they might create as subclasses of the Instrument class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0b954ade-d239-4124-8e0e-a1dba70da283",
        "lesson_activity.key": "5802724c-42c0-4be7-8322-5185e1e19edb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d675c2a5-9d72-4bd7-8a56-2a42a0f3f2fc",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We know that the `Painter` class works as the software engineers who wrote it intended, so we don't want to add new code to this class that might break it. Now that we know about inheritance, we can instead extend it to create a subclass of the `Painter` class and add any new code that we want.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Writing a Subclass",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d675c2a5-9d72-4bd7-8a56-2a42a0f3f2fc",
        "lesson_activity.key": "5802724c-42c0-4be7-8322-5185e1e19edb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "bd4edc51-155a-4860-8397-b32142f63e78",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Do This:** Demonstrate how to create a new class in Java Lab:\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> The New File button\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Enter the name of the class\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Write the class header\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Add the `extends` keyword\n\n**Do This:** Explain the structure of a Java program with multiple classes:\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> The class to create objects from\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> The ***tester*** class with the `main` method\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 1 on Code Studio to complete Levels 1, 2, and 3. Students complete a Check for Understanding on Level 1, then continue to Level 2 to write their `PainterPlus` class. Students create an object of their `PainterPlus` class then continue to Level 3 to use their `PainterPlus`object.",
        "progression_name": "Practice: Creating PainterPlus",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Check for Understanding and practice levels can be used as formative assessments to gauge understanding of vocabulary presented in the lesson and writing a class that extends a superclass."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "bd4edc51-155a-4860-8397-b32142f63e78",
        "lesson_activity.key": "5802724c-42c0-4be7-8322-5185e1e19edb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "fddac857-3418-4a05-8c38-314511085dd5",
      "position": 13,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What happened when you called `Painter` class methods? Why do you think this happened?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students note that their `PainterPlus` class can use the methods in the `Painter` class. They realize that this happens because the `PainterPlus` class shares the same attributes and behaviors as the `Painter` class.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Hold That Thought strategy to allow students to write down their thoughts on paper first. Emphasize that they do not need to write complete sentences – they can write a few words, bullet points, draw a quick sketch, or anything else that will help them gather and recall their thoughts when it is time to share with the class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "fddac857-3418-4a05-8c38-314511085dd5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "5802724c-42c0-4be7-8322-5185e1e19edb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "cdf96d1a-4a55-4d23-bf68-b39782ca76e7",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Right now, our `PainterPlus` objects can only do the same things a `Painter` object can do. In the next lesson, we will add a new method to the `PainterPlus` class so that our `PainterPlus` objects can do things that a `Painter` object can't do.",
        "name": "PainterPlus Behaviors",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "cdf96d1a-4a55-4d23-bf68-b39782ca76e7",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d2074b31-5313-4c20-b463-8b636b5fd038"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c4e1be98-f934-4cc4-bebd-fa9ebb2646c3",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What are some things you want a `PainterPlus` object to do that a `Painter` object can't do?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students share ideas of methods they could add to the `PainterPlus` class, such as a method to turn right, navigate faster, or take all of the paint from a paint bucket.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the concepts covered in this lesson.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Question of the Day.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Key Vocabulary"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c4e1be98-f934-4cc4-bebd-fa9ebb2646c3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d2074b31-5313-4c20-b463-8b636b5fd038"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f3089929-8e6e-46a0-950f-d8cc38657b34",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "---"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f3089929-8e6e-46a0-950f-d8cc38657b34",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d2074b31-5313-4c20-b463-8b636b5fd038"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "dba9b058-d8e3-472b-a31c-93f3b99a1c9f",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "*Check For Understanding Question(s) and solutions can be found in each lesson on Code Studio. These questions can be used for an exit ticket.*",
        "name": "Assessment: Check for Understanding",
        "progression_name": "Check for Understanding"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "dba9b058-d8e3-472b-a31c-93f3b99a1c9f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d2074b31-5313-4c20-b463-8b636b5fd038"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4bf59ad9-7240-4674-8236-29720468b31d",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What do you know or remember about functions?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students share what they recall about functions from a previous computer science course, such as Computer Science Discoveries or Computer Science Principles. They note that they wrote functions to represent a specific task that they could call in their programs as many times as they needed. Students may also recall specifying parameters for functions to make these more flexible for different inputs.",
        "name": "Functions",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If your students took Computer Science Principles previously, prompt them to recall how they used functions in their Create Performance Task or other programs they created in that course. Ask students about the purpose of these functions and the benefits from creating functions.\n\nUse the Retrieve-Pair-Share strategy to facilitate this discussion by directing students to write down their thoughts and ideas on the Unit 1 Guide first, then pair up students to compare their answers and expand their notes. This allows time for individual processing and idea generation before sharing thoughts with others. Ask students to share the ideas they discussed with their partners as a class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4bf59ad9-7240-4674-8236-29720468b31d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "0b7fa7da-cfa6-4b6d-8b26-86040b63e34b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a5e57ac7-fa29-4f6b-8c98-3f2c0ac87e7b",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Introduction"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a5e57ac7-fa29-4f6b-8c98-3f2c0ac87e7b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d04bfe94-151b-460e-a023-c27bc9405382"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "69cdd8c4-4ce2-4f3e-88d2-b4865ca358dd",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Software engineers often create subclasses to have additional methods or attributes. We created a subclass of the `Painter` class so we can have a new type of `Painter` that can do things that a `Painter` object cannot do. Before adding new methods to our `PainterPlus` class, we need to know how to write a method.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "69cdd8c4-4ce2-4f3e-88d2-b4865ca358dd",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d04bfe94-151b-460e-a023-c27bc9405382"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8535ca2e-ecdc-4ef7-8685-0ae4a48cf4a9",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 1 on Code Studio to predict the program's outcome, then run the program to compare their predictions to the actual outcome.",
        "progression_name": "Predict and Run: Writing Methods"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8535ca2e-ecdc-4ef7-8685-0ae4a48cf4a9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d04bfe94-151b-460e-a023-c27bc9405382"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f0218247-c524-4226-9a66-3a8e20baa4f7",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What did you notice about the code in this program?*\n* *What do you wonder about the code in this program?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students notice that the `PainterPlus` class has a new method called `square()` that moves and turns a `PainterPlus` object in a square. Students may also notice that when this method calls `Painter` class methods, it does not specify an object. Students might wonder how to write methods for the algorithms they have written or about the components of the method."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f0218247-c524-4226-9a66-3a8e20baa4f7",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d04bfe94-151b-460e-a023-c27bc9405382"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "760addc1-95a0-4180-8135-86a42efd441e",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We previously learned that the `paint()` method in the `Painter` class has a parameter for a paint color. When we call the `paint()` method, we provide a string literal with the paint color we want to use as the argument. When we write methods, we can write methods either with or without parameters. Let's take a look at how this works.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Void Methods",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "760addc1-95a0-4180-8135-86a42efd441e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d04bfe94-151b-460e-a023-c27bc9405382"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4d44f98a-158b-4949-8b15-fc82b2b43724",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Group:** Place students in pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 2 on Code Studio to complete Levels 2 through 4. Students investigate the program by modifying the program as prompted and observing the results.",
        "progression_name": "Investigate and Modify: Void Methods"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4d44f98a-158b-4949-8b15-fc82b2b43724",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d04bfe94-151b-460e-a023-c27bc9405382"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5867fcfa-a94f-4fef-90eb-d1cac6c1dff3",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students share what they discovered from the modifications they made to the code."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5867fcfa-a94f-4fef-90eb-d1cac6c1dff3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d04bfe94-151b-460e-a023-c27bc9405382"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "12314248-953a-4280-99a8-22bf723acae6",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "This `PainterPlus` class has a new method called `square()` that moves and turns a `Painter` object in a square. We can see in the tester class that the `PainterPlus` object is now able to call this method as well as the methods in the `Painter` class to navigate and paint in The Neighborhood. Before we start adding our own methods to our `PainterPlus` classes, let's find out how we write a method in Java.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Writing a Method",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "12314248-953a-4280-99a8-22bf723acae6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d04bfe94-151b-460e-a023-c27bc9405382"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c7e3d934-cfe6-4f08-9e58-d24cb00baa62",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Show the video – *Writing a Method*.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Videos are used throughout the curriculum to spark discussions, supplement key concepts with additional explanations and examples, and expose students to the various roles and backgrounds of individuals in computer science.\n\nWhile interacting with the video, turn on closed captioning so students can also read along as they watch.\n\nTo encourage active engagement and reflection, use one or more of the strategies discussed in the [**Guide to Curriculum Videos**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1FqIUpJg6MrgdtbFGLobSojOz0u1m5Jge1nMAjUqI5ZM/edit?usp=sharing)."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c7e3d934-cfe6-4f08-9e58-d24cb00baa62",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d04bfe94-151b-460e-a023-c27bc9405382"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4be17362-af48-4931-b033-297018ae52c9",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Do This:** Explain the components of a method signature:\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> The keyword `public`\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> The ***return type***\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> The name of the method\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Define ***method signature***\n\n**Do This:** Explain how methods are called:\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Java looks for method in the class\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Define ***return***",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Point out to students that since the method has a `void` return type, no value or information is provided. The code in the method is executed and then continues to the next line of code. In this example, after completing the instructions for the `move()` method, the program returns to where `move()` was called and continues to the `takePaint()` method."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4be17362-af48-4931-b033-297018ae52c9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d04bfe94-151b-460e-a023-c27bc9405382"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "bc91a0e7-02a0-47bd-a585-79913c71a070",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What do you think the word `void` means? How does this relate to the return type of a method?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students share definitions for void, such as nothing or empty. Students suggest that this might mean that the method does not return anything.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Ask additional guiding questions to help students make the connection between their understanding of the word `void` and the return type of a method being `void`. For example:\n* *The return type in the method signature specifies the type of value to return from the method. If the method is `void`, what does that mean about the value that is being returned?*"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "bc91a0e7-02a0-47bd-a585-79913c71a070",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d04bfe94-151b-460e-a023-c27bc9405382"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ea00adb8-ded5-4591-a39a-06d3f7240f6f",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***void***.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that a subclass can access methods in the superclass, but a superclass cannot access methods in the subclass."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ea00adb8-ded5-4591-a39a-06d3f7240f6f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d04bfe94-151b-460e-a023-c27bc9405382"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7dd1355a-8e59-45fb-893a-88e486ca223e",
      "position": 13,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We're almost ready to start writing some methods in our `PainterPlus` class! We can add a method to turn right in our `PainterPlus` class and write methods for the algorithms we wrote before so we can easily call them whenever we want.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Writing Methods in PainterPlus",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7dd1355a-8e59-45fb-893a-88e486ca223e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d04bfe94-151b-460e-a023-c27bc9405382"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d68ea04e-1679-4a13-9c9d-a009914a5717",
      "position": 14,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Do This:** Explain how to write a method in a class:\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Must be inside the opening and closing curly braces for the class\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Write the method signature then a set of curly braces\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Write the code the method should execute inside these curly braces\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Since the class is the blueprint for an object, we do not refer to a specific object when calling methods in the current class or a superclass\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 5 on Code Studio to complete Levels 5, 6, and 7. Students complete a Check for Understanding on Level 5, then continue to Level 6 to write and use the `turnRight()` method. Students complete a choice level on Level 7 to write an additional method in their `PainterPlus` class.",
        "progression_name": "Practice: Writing Methods",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Check for Understanding and practice levels can be used as formative assessments to gauge understanding of vocabulary presented in the lesson and writing methods in a subclass."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d68ea04e-1679-4a13-9c9d-a009914a5717",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d04bfe94-151b-460e-a023-c27bc9405382"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "672caafe-be8f-432e-87c2-5198b2454f07",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Our `PainterPlus` objects can now do everything `Painter` objects can do and more! Software engineers use inheritance and methods in their programs to help make their code more organized and easy to maintain and update. These also make it easy for us to add new features to our programs so we don't have to rewrite the same code over and over and so we don't have to worry about breaking any existing code.",
        "name": "Glows, Grows, Want-to-Knows",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "672caafe-be8f-432e-87c2-5198b2454f07",
        "lesson_activity.key": "36c39ba3-d200-43d8-9b40-e1000cb5787b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6b0c84b3-1b55-4552-9bf4-e16a20bb80ca",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What was awesome about writing your code?*\n* *What is one action you can take to improve your code?*\n* *What questions do you have about today?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students share aspects of their program they enjoyed or how they solved the problem and identify areas of improvement to strengthen their programming skills. Students also share any questions or misconceptions they may have.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Glows, Grows, Want-to-Knows is a strategy to help students identify their strengths and areas of improvement and share any questions or misconceptions."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6b0c84b3-1b55-4552-9bf4-e16a20bb80ca",
        "lesson_activity.key": "36c39ba3-d200-43d8-9b40-e1000cb5787b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "639af56c-d0f9-41e9-93fd-4f80c10cac94",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the concepts covered in this lesson.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Question of the Day.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Key Vocabulary"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "639af56c-d0f9-41e9-93fd-4f80c10cac94",
        "lesson_activity.key": "36c39ba3-d200-43d8-9b40-e1000cb5787b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "fb743da8-a572-4a48-85b5-a1488d9d61cf",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "---"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "fb743da8-a572-4a48-85b5-a1488d9d61cf",
        "lesson_activity.key": "36c39ba3-d200-43d8-9b40-e1000cb5787b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "119138be-d945-4a22-9e45-184dc7af61a1",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "*Check For Understanding Question(s) and solutions can be found in each lesson on Code Studio. These questions can be used for an exit ticket.*",
        "name": "Assessment: Check for Understanding",
        "progression_name": "Check for Understanding"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "119138be-d945-4a22-9e45-184dc7af61a1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "36c39ba3-d200-43d8-9b40-e1000cb5787b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "cd3edb00-d358-43ff-85e4-0f1de9bbd84a",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Imagine you are going on a weekend trip, and you have a checklist of things to ensure a smooth trip. Before you can decide your trip is possible, what are some preconditions you need to meet? What postconditions would show that you had a successful and enjoyable trip?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Without explicitly defining preconditions and conditions, students are able to apply this vocabulary to a familiar, engaging topic. Students share their thoughts on planning their trip and what a successful trip would look like. By doing so, students are able to connect their understanding of preconditions and postconditions in real-life scenarios with the Java style lessons they are learning.",
        "name": "Software Engineers",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "There is space on the Unit 1 Guide for students to individually reflect and respond to the prompt. Encourage students to share their reflections and progress as a class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "cd3edb00-d358-43ff-85e4-0f1de9bbd84a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "92e1c0ce-15a5-48c3-894d-40bd81c0894b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "54cbbf8e-fbfe-46d1-bfe6-35f381797bb9",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Style and Documentation"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "54cbbf8e-fbfe-46d1-bfe6-35f381797bb9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9de0d264-c229-4208-9657-aac9839714b9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b1a29d22-d22c-43bd-aa35-777937ce60d3",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We have learned a lot about writing code, and our programs are becoming more complex as we learn new concepts. As our programs grow, we must write code that is easy to read and navigate. Software engineers follow guidelines to write their code and use various tools to keep track of their work, access code that they want to reuse in a different program, and request and give feedback.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b1a29d22-d22c-43bd-aa35-777937ce60d3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9de0d264-c229-4208-9657-aac9839714b9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8e9043e9-2106-418c-839f-c83172287cb8",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Group:** Place students in pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 1 on Code Studio. Students use Levels 1 and 2 to explore good and bad programming styles and multi-line comments with their partners.",
        "progression_name": "Investigate: Programming Style"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8e9043e9-2106-418c-839f-c83172287cb8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9de0d264-c229-4208-9657-aac9839714b9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "495ec233-7063-43f4-856c-1f9ca5154138",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What did you notice in the programming style examples?*\n* *Why was one programming style better than the other?*\n* *Why would using good programming style and comments be important?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students identify aspects of both example programs that made it easy or difficult to read and understand. Students note that the good program example indented blocks of code and included comments to explain the purpose of code segments.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *programming style* and discuss the example guidelines.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *documentation*.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *commit*.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Why would we want to commit our code?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students suggest that committing their code allows them to save snapshots of their code that they can revert back to when needed. The notes on each commit makes it easy for them to find the version they are looking for and quickly identify the changes they have made to their code.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Hold That Thought strategy to allow students to write down their thoughts on paper first. Emphasize that they do not need to write complete sentences – they can write a few words, bullet points, draw a quick sketch, or anything else that will help them gather and recall their thoughts when it is time to share with the class.\n\nStudents may not see the benefits of committing their code right away. Ask students about what they saw in the Version History after committing their code and how this might be useful."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "495ec233-7063-43f4-856c-1f9ca5154138",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9de0d264-c229-4208-9657-aac9839714b9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "56361017-6b5d-4e62-904f-cbe4fab595f3",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "56361017-6b5d-4e62-904f-cbe4fab595f3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9de0d264-c229-4208-9657-aac9839714b9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8c99db2a-2b03-4e9c-8afe-025edb69edc9",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students work with their partner to brainstorm guidelines for programming style and comments. Have students share the guidelines they create as a class.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "There is space on the Guided Notes for students to brainstorm guidelines for programming style and comments.\n\nCreate a class list of guidelines for programming style and comments on chart paper to post in the classroom or on a slide or digital whiteboard that can be shared with the class. Remind students to refer to these guidelines when they are working on activities and projects."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8c99db2a-2b03-4e9c-8afe-025edb69edc9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9de0d264-c229-4208-9657-aac9839714b9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "93c1837b-6313-4ac6-946f-917b2ec63137",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "93c1837b-6313-4ac6-946f-917b2ec63137",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9de0d264-c229-4208-9657-aac9839714b9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0be12719-f74f-4581-8e47-5dc3eaf19467",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "When software engineers plan an algorithm, they take into consideration things that must be true for the algorithm to work and things that must be true after the algorithm finishes. This helps us to decide if we need to check for things like invalid values before executing the algorithm so we don't have unexpected results or errors.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Preconditions and Postconditions",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0be12719-f74f-4581-8e47-5dc3eaf19467",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9de0d264-c229-4208-9657-aac9839714b9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1ae1d956-e114-478c-ae01-6fa840acad36",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *precondition*.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *postcondition*.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Point out how the precondition and postcondition for the code segment are noted in the method comment. Emphasize to students about indicating these in the comments to provide documentation about the purpose and functionality of a method.\n\nAsk students to consider whether these preconditions and postconditions are currently being satisfied in the example code segment. Have students share ideas for how to improve the code segment to satisfy these conditions."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1ae1d956-e114-478c-ae01-6fa840acad36",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9de0d264-c229-4208-9657-aac9839714b9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "75b3c42f-868c-4f08-b598-2791e4dcbe17",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "75b3c42f-868c-4f08-b598-2791e4dcbe17",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9de0d264-c229-4208-9657-aac9839714b9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "bda19290-35ee-4b88-85cd-2d1155632491",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Discuss:** *Consider this scenario. What would be the precondition for this algorithm? What would be the postcondition?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students suggest preconditions for the algorithm, such as making sure that the `Painter` has paint. Students also suggest postconditions for the algorithm, such as that a square is painted as expected.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If students struggle to identify preconditions and postconditions for the algorithm, ask additional probing questions to help them determine conditions that must be true before and after the algorithm executes. For example:\n* *Are there any restrictions on the initial position or direction of the Painter?*\n* *Does the Painter only paint on empty spaces? Or can it paint over existing colors?*\n* *Does the Painter need to have a particular amount of paint before executing the algorithm?*"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "bda19290-35ee-4b88-85cd-2d1155632491",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9de0d264-c229-4208-9657-aac9839714b9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "508116f5-6e2d-45a2-b49f-bd57bef562e6",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "508116f5-6e2d-45a2-b49f-bd57bef562e6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9de0d264-c229-4208-9657-aac9839714b9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a41e6b5c-3199-4e1f-9725-ababef9c449e",
      "position": 13,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Preconditions and postconditions are useful for identifying what conditions must be met for a method to execute as intended and the expected outcome. Software engineers write method code to satisfy the postconditions when preconditions are met.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a41e6b5c-3199-4e1f-9725-ababef9c449e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9de0d264-c229-4208-9657-aac9839714b9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1dd44b4a-bb82-4d92-bfcc-de2df9a18e55",
      "position": 14,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Consider this method. What should we add or modify to make sure the preconditions are met so we can satisfy the postconditions?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students suggest adding an `if` statement to check if the `Painter` has sufficient paint.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to demonstrate a solution.\n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1dd44b4a-bb82-4d92-bfcc-de2df9a18e55",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9de0d264-c229-4208-9657-aac9839714b9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "436f30f8-707d-4d70-be9c-242bcbe1bb69",
      "position": 15,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Software engineers spend a lot of time reading other people's code and providing feedback. Throughout this course, you will use code reviews as a tool for improving your coding and collaboration skills.",
        "duration": "20",
        "name": "Code Reviews",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "436f30f8-707d-4d70-be9c-242bcbe1bb69",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9de0d264-c229-4208-9657-aac9839714b9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a841e850-34fe-4cf9-b3f3-3f4ef4f4183c",
      "position": 16,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Show the video – *Software Engineering: Code Reviews*.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Videos are used throughout the curriculum to spark discussions, supplement key concepts with additional explanations and examples, and expose students to the various roles and backgrounds of individuals in computer science.\n\nWhile interacting with the video, turn on closed captioning so students can also read along as they watch.\n\nTo encourage active engagement and reflection, use one or more of the strategies discussed in the [**Guide to Curriculum Videos**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1FqIUpJg6MrgdtbFGLobSojOz0u1m5Jge1nMAjUqI5ZM/edit?usp=sharing)."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a841e850-34fe-4cf9-b3f3-3f4ef4f4183c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9de0d264-c229-4208-9657-aac9839714b9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e66e09cd-0bcb-4e14-82be-6bc12eb97331",
      "position": 17,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e66e09cd-0bcb-4e14-82be-6bc12eb97331",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9de0d264-c229-4208-9657-aac9839714b9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a8e620d2-04a7-4f54-8e96-cc396b848a6d",
      "position": 18,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What kind of feedback is helpful when you are learning something new or working on an assignment?*\n* *What kind of feedback is not helpful?*\n\n**Discussion Goal: Students share examples of feedback that was helpful and feedback that was not helpful and make connections to scenarios where they received both helpful and unhelpful feedback. Students identify things that make feedback unhelpful, such as not being specific or clear.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Ask students why they considered the feedback unhelpful or what they wish the person giving the feedback had said. Connect with students by sharing an example of your own."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a8e620d2-04a7-4f54-8e96-cc396b848a6d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9de0d264-c229-4208-9657-aac9839714b9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "efe75089-0f8a-4bd9-a5fb-82c7ee3e5817",
      "position": 19,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "efe75089-0f8a-4bd9-a5fb-82c7ee3e5817",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9de0d264-c229-4208-9657-aac9839714b9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "139b9827-0253-4188-96c7-191022d7ce6b",
      "position": 20,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Software engineers get feedback from their peers everyday to help them improve their code and ensure that they are meeting the program's requirements. Not only is it important for us to receive helpful feedback when we are learning something new or working on an assignment, it is also important when we're developing programs. Software engineers do this using a process called a code review.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "139b9827-0253-4188-96c7-191022d7ce6b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9de0d264-c229-4208-9657-aac9839714b9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d566a469-c342-495c-beca-b80b28cb2215",
      "position": 21,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce and define *code review*.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Give each student a copy of the How to Conduct a Code Review resource.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce TAG for providing feedback in code reviews and point out the sentence starters on the How to Conduct a Code Review resource.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to introduce the Code Review Call and Response.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "The Call and Response strategy helps build community and create routines in the classroom."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d566a469-c342-495c-beca-b80b28cb2215",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9de0d264-c229-4208-9657-aac9839714b9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "563545fe-3a38-4607-8601-20dd9fa30bdf",
      "position": 22,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "563545fe-3a38-4607-8601-20dd9fa30bdf",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9de0d264-c229-4208-9657-aac9839714b9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "00eadc89-9ab1-4bf2-8435-0ca1b208db54",
      "position": 23,
      "properties": {
        "description": "You have been placed in code review groups to review each other's code and make revisions to your program based on the feedback you receive.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "00eadc89-9ab1-4bf2-8435-0ca1b208db54",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9de0d264-c229-4208-9657-aac9839714b9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a69b2c60-380f-4b4d-94ed-3f129e80138d",
      "position": 24,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to have students participate in the Code Review Call and Response.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 3 on Code Studio. Students choose a choice level to add comments to the code and practice giving and receiving feedback in a code review.",
        "progression_name": "Practice: Conducting a Code Review",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Actively encourage students to not just solve the programming challenge, but to also add appropriate documentation in the form of comments, preconditions, and postconditions. Similarly, when students are reviewing their peers, ask them to check not for “correct” solutions, but for code that has strong documentation."
          },
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The practice levels can be used as a formative assessment to check that students appropriately use comments to document code and use TAG to structure feedback."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a69b2c60-380f-4b4d-94ed-3f129e80138d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9de0d264-c229-4208-9657-aac9839714b9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "762f0707-8583-4b2e-8b0a-3b479ae70a92",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Good programming style and code reviews are an important part of a software engineer's work.",
        "name": "Impacts of Bad Code",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "762f0707-8583-4b2e-8b0a-3b479ae70a92",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d746fc25-410e-44a9-bfba-463a2291bb38"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "890385c2-8b65-40be-a246-d03f0ddd0d59",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What surprises you about this visual? What do you want to know more about?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students share aspects of the visual that surprise them, such as the amount of time spent on fixing errors. They might ask questions about why so much time is spent on finding and fixing errors.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Approximately $85 billion is lost from developer time spent on bad code each year. How can software engineers minimize this time?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students consider the broader role of a software engineer and the various tasks they complete as part of their work. Students identify strategies to minimize time spent on bad code, such as using good programming style and planning and reviewing code.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the concepts covered in this lesson. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Question of the Day.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Key Vocabulary"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "890385c2-8b65-40be-a246-d03f0ddd0d59",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d746fc25-410e-44a9-bfba-463a2291bb38"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "444142df-ce4c-48ac-a4ab-39a437b0c3b9",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "---"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "444142df-ce4c-48ac-a4ab-39a437b0c3b9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d746fc25-410e-44a9-bfba-463a2291bb38"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f83c79b7-4513-4909-b219-176e8358fb10",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "*Check For Understanding Question(s) and solutions can be found in each lesson on Code Studio. These questions can be used for an exit ticket.*",
        "name": "Assessment: Check for Understanding",
        "progression_name": "Check for Understanding"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f83c79b7-4513-4909-b219-176e8358fb10",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d746fc25-410e-44a9-bfba-463a2291bb38"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a871cfd0-97af-4989-8bda-6fc96374dfb5",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "When we are finding and fixing errors in our programs, we are debugging our code. You likely learned about bugs and debugging in your previous computer science class and some strategies for debugging your programs.",
        "name": "Bugs and Debugging",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a871cfd0-97af-4989-8bda-6fc96374dfb5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d3eeb4e5-324a-4029-abe2-00026f77e811"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0aab6854-3830-4d23-adff-728537394250",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What do you know or remember about bugs and debugging?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students recall that bugs are errors in a program and that debugging is the process of finding and fixing bugs. Students may share scenarios or examples from Computer Science Discoveries (CSD), Computer Science Principles (CSP), or other computer science course of the types of bugs they encountered or the debugging strategies they used.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Retrieve-Pair-Share strategy to facilitate this discussion by directing students to write down their thoughts and ideas on the Unit 1 Guide first, then pair up students to compare their answers and expand their notes. This allows time for individual processing and idea generation before sharing thoughts with others. Ask students to share the ideas they discussed with their partners as a class.\n\nPrompt students to recall the types of bugs they encountered in previous computer science courses and how they found and fixed these errors. Ask students to share the debugging strategies they used in these courses or that they have used so far in The Neighborhood."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0aab6854-3830-4d23-adff-728537394250",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d3eeb4e5-324a-4029-abe2-00026f77e811"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "51a182bc-bcf0-49d9-8237-1ad0b30620c5",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Introduction"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "51a182bc-bcf0-49d9-8237-1ad0b30620c5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "16f6ee5f-56d9-4b88-a445-3f6488f880a8"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "78bcebec-ea03-48c0-b18f-b5a8f0c55cb9",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Software engineers use a variety of strategies to debug their programs. One strategy software engineers use is to print information about their program as it is running to help them track changing values and identify errors. Let's take a look at how we can do this in Java.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "78bcebec-ea03-48c0-b18f-b5a8f0c55cb9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "16f6ee5f-56d9-4b88-a445-3f6488f880a8"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9a358aea-1972-46e4-a235-7109ec59dc8a",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 1 on Code Studio to predict the program's outcome, then run the program to compare their predictions to the actual outcome.",
        "progression_name": "Predict and Run: Variables and Printing"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9a358aea-1972-46e4-a235-7109ec59dc8a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "16f6ee5f-56d9-4b88-a445-3f6488f880a8"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d6b675d2-f855-472a-8eee-9daa25599e69",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What did you notice about the code in this program?*\n* *What do you wonder about the code in this program?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students notice that the program creates several variables and calls new methods in the `Painter` class. The values of the variables are printed to the console while the `Painter` object is moving and painting in The Neighborhood. Students may wonder about the syntax for creating variables, printing their values, or the new methods in the `Painter` class that get information about a `Painter` object.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Students likely have learned about variables in a previous computer science course, such as Computer Science Discoveries (CSD) or Computer Science Principles (CSP). Ask students how these variables are similar and different from those they have seen before. You can also prompt students to recall how these variables work and hypothesize if the functionality of variables is the same in Java."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d6b675d2-f855-472a-8eee-9daa25599e69",
        "lesson_activity.key": "16f6ee5f-56d9-4b88-a445-3f6488f880a8"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5c05d01e-eff6-4609-8210-e7b41d8d0f09",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Do This:** Explain the functionality of a variable:\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Define ***variable***\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Define ***data type***",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Since the methods students work with in this lesson return either an `int` or a `String`, the focus is only on these types. Other data types will be discussed in future lessons."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5c05d01e-eff6-4609-8210-e7b41d8d0f09",
        "lesson_activity.key": "16f6ee5f-56d9-4b88-a445-3f6488f880a8"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3ed8993f-66a8-42ed-85b8-4f80ccca492c",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Do This:** Explain the syntax for declaring a variable and assigning a value:\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Define ***declaration***\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> The variable gets the value returned from the method",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Be careful not to refer to the assignment operator as \"*equals*\" since it does not represent equality. When reading a line of code with the assignment operator (the `=`), use the word \"*gets*\" to refer to the assignment operator. For example, \"`currentX` *gets the value returned from the call to the `getX()` method*.\""
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3ed8993f-66a8-42ed-85b8-4f80ccca492c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "16f6ee5f-56d9-4b88-a445-3f6488f880a8"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5f561161-b4f3-4053-a3ed-e8eff5c2454d",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We have learned to use the problem solving process to break down a problem and develop algorithms. We can also use the problem solving process to find and fix errors in a program.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Debugging Strategies",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5f561161-b4f3-4053-a3ed-e8eff5c2454d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "16f6ee5f-56d9-4b88-a445-3f6488f880a8"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2200106c-214e-422a-b6aa-8a86339fc3dd",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Group:** Place students in pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each pair a copy of the Investigate: Debugging in The Neighborhood handout.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 2 on Code Studio to investigate the program and complete the Investigate: Debugging in The Neighborhood handout.",
        "progression_name": "Investigate and Modify: Debugging"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2200106c-214e-422a-b6aa-8a86339fc3dd",
        "lesson_activity.key": "16f6ee5f-56d9-4b88-a445-3f6488f880a8"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2228dc20-0e6c-44ab-8ce4-00506a7913e5",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students share what they discovered from the modifications they made to the code and their responses on the Investigate: Debugging in The Neighborhood handout.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Show the video – *Printing in Java*.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Videos are used throughout the curriculum to spark discussions, supplement key concepts with additional explanations and examples, and expose students to the various roles and backgrounds of individuals in computer science.\n\nWhile interacting with the video, turn on closed captioning so students can also read along as they watch.\n\nTo encourage active engagement and reflection, use one or more of the strategies discussed in the [**Guide to Curriculum Videos**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1FqIUpJg6MrgdtbFGLobSojOz0u1m5Jge1nMAjUqI5ZM/edit?usp=sharing)."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2228dc20-0e6c-44ab-8ce4-00506a7913e5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "16f6ee5f-56d9-4b88-a445-3f6488f880a8"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6789531d-14f9-4837-874a-2152553b7513",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Do This:** Explain how to print in Java:\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> The `System.out.print()` method\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> The `System.out.println()` method\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How might variables, the methods that return information about a `Painter` object, and printing be helpful when we are writing our code?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students suggest that these can be used to find errors that are not immediately obvious. They can use the values to track a `Painter` object's position, the direction it is facing, and how much paint it has to identify where the error happens and find the specific line of code that is causing the error.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Hold That Thought strategy to allow students to write down their thoughts on paper first. Emphasize that they do not need to write complete sentences – they can write a few words, bullet points, draw a quick sketch, or anything else that will help them gather and recall their thoughts when it is time to share with the class.\n\nAsk students how they used variables, the `Painter` class methods, and printing in the Investigate level to debug the program. Prompt students to share how this helped them find the errors."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6789531d-14f9-4837-874a-2152553b7513",
        "lesson_activity.key": "16f6ee5f-56d9-4b88-a445-3f6488f880a8"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6c2b2eb8-77b2-4390-91d7-14e7a286e09a",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Now that we've learned some strategies for debugging programs using variables, printing, and methods in the `Painter` class, let's try debugging a program using the problem solving process. Be sure to also use the tests to get feedback about what the program is supposed to do to help you identify where you might need to look.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Debugging in The Neighborhood",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6c2b2eb8-77b2-4390-91d7-14e7a286e09a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "16f6ee5f-56d9-4b88-a445-3f6488f880a8"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8d1b5845-f322-4e67-b80d-aa78cdb2e933",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 3 on Code Studio to complete Levels 3 and 4. Students complete a Check for Understanding on Level 3, then continue to Level 4 to complete a choice level to use the problem solving process and printing to debug the program.",
        "progression_name": "Practice: Debugging in The Neighborhood",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Check for Understanding and practice levels can be used as formative assessments to gauge understanding of variables and applying the problem solving process to debug a program."
          },
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If students get stuck, have them write down the steps in the problem solving process. Have them note the problem, the steps they want to try to solve the problem, and the results of the changes they make. You can also have students work with a partner to explain their ideas and reasoning to help them work through the process."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8d1b5845-f322-4e67-b80d-aa78cdb2e933",
        "lesson_activity.key": "16f6ee5f-56d9-4b88-a445-3f6488f880a8"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4faea35e-827d-4090-b9b7-d67db9067a01",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We learned a lot about debugging strategies today! Let's recap some of the key concepts from today's lesson.",
        "name": "Closing the Loop",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4faea35e-827d-4090-b9b7-d67db9067a01",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e5107e96-2eee-422a-8b19-952c010da1f6"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "38a6b60c-67fd-4a98-af53-2a69af4e1f33",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What is the difference between methods that return a value and `void` methods?*\n* *What parts of this lesson were similar to strategies you have used to solve other problems?*\n* *What were you confident about? What would you like to practice?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students explain the difference between methods that return a value and `void` methods and make connections to the methods in the `Painter` class. Students suggest examples of strategies they have used to solve other problems, such as going through a solution one step at a time or tracing the values of variables in previous computer science classes or math classes. Students share concepts from the lesson that they are confident about and concepts they might be confused about.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the concepts covered in this lesson.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Question of the Day.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Key Vocabulary"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "38a6b60c-67fd-4a98-af53-2a69af4e1f33",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e5107e96-2eee-422a-8b19-952c010da1f6"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8798e3e1-ca49-457d-b072-eba46734e85a",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "---"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8798e3e1-ca49-457d-b072-eba46734e85a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e5107e96-2eee-422a-8b19-952c010da1f6"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ff214bc6-48a3-42e9-b064-05d423a84840",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "*Check For Understanding Question(s) and solutions can be found in each lesson on Code Studio. These questions can be used for an exit ticket.*",
        "name": "Assessment: Check for Understanding",
        "progression_name": "Check for Understanding"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ff214bc6-48a3-42e9-b064-05d423a84840",
