      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2a93e09b-cea6-4c02-9be7-7e82f3c11aa2",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "To assign questions from the AP Classroom Question Bank that align with this lesson, create a custom quiz in AP Classroom by searching the Question Bank for the Essential Knowledge statements listed at the top of this lesson plan. You can find instructions and video demonstrations to do this on [**AP Central**](https://apcentral.collegeboard.org/instructional-resources/ap-classroom).\n\nThe following Topic Questions in AP Classroom can be assigned as a formative assessment for this lesson:\n\n* Topic Questions 1.1\n\n**Note:** *Some Learning Objectives and Essential Knowledge statements in the suggested Topic Questions are covered in later units.*",
        "name": "AP Classroom Topic Questions"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2a93e09b-cea6-4c02-9be7-7e82f3c11aa2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e5107e96-2eee-422a-8b19-952c010da1f6"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4f6237c6-6646-4803-86fa-a48d5d15d41b",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "In the previous lesson, you started developing a program for Joyful Pastries to help the owner manage the desserts they sell at their food truck. This food truck is actually named after Joy Buolamwini, a poet of code who uses art and research to challenge bias in programs using artificial intelligence.",
        "name": "Poet of Code",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4f6237c6-6646-4803-86fa-a48d5d15d41b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "02f417e8-5762-42ab-8003-cea788ce9146"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "46121314-a23c-44f7-ae8c-7070963b36b2",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What does this quote make you think about or wonder?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students make connections between the quote and scenarios they have encountered or things they have learned in the course so far. These might include sharing their thoughts on real-world scenarios and issues and how this quote relates to these.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "You can also show students' parts of the [**Poet of Code**](https://www.poetofcode.com/) website, such as a video from one of the campaigns or parts of one of her talks. Choose one that you feel would be most appropriate and engaging for your students to show different applications of computer science, current issues, and spark inspiration as \"poets of code.\""
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "46121314-a23c-44f7-ae8c-7070963b36b2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "02f417e8-5762-42ab-8003-cea788ce9146"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "445ade47-3708-49ea-98e7-37c0a4bca350",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Introduction"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "445ade47-3708-49ea-98e7-37c0a4bca350",
        "lesson_activity.key": "78bdc6b5-598a-4639-923d-2f57eea8b56d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a997257e-49e8-46cd-9190-4567fb955acf",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "In the previous lesson, we declared instance variables to represent attributes of an object. Now that we have these instance variables, we need to tell Java what values these attributes should have when we create an object. Let's find out how we can do this.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a997257e-49e8-46cd-9190-4567fb955acf",
        "lesson_activity.key": "78bdc6b5-598a-4639-923d-2f57eea8b56d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d79b973a-7d7c-4f68-95f1-b6ae9b881b53",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 1 on Code Studio to predict the program's outcome, then run the program to compare their predictions to the actual outcome.",
        "progression_name": "Predict and Run: No-Argument Constructors"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d79b973a-7d7c-4f68-95f1-b6ae9b881b53",
        "lesson_activity.key": "78bdc6b5-598a-4639-923d-2f57eea8b56d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ba15063d-ed33-4a5c-8388-9ca4b342a2db",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What did you notice about the code in this program?*\n* *What do you wonder about the code in this program?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students notice the constructor that assigns values to each of the instance variables. Students might wonder how these values are determined."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ba15063d-ed33-4a5c-8388-9ca4b342a2db",
        "lesson_activity.key": "78bdc6b5-598a-4639-923d-2f57eea8b56d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "67d1a5ef-3819-4325-b4c3-6e64f008d336",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Recall how objects are instantiated by calling the constructor.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide and explain the flow of control when a constructor is called.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***no-argument constructor***.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 2 on Code Studio to complete Levels 2, 3, and 4. Students investigate the program, make changes to the program as prompted, and observe the results.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Constructors",
        "progression_name": "Investigate and Modify: Constructors"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "67d1a5ef-3819-4325-b4c3-6e64f008d336",
        "lesson_activity.key": "78bdc6b5-598a-4639-923d-2f57eea8b56d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4701a439-dcbb-405b-a3c1-51a4cc4ef999",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students share what they discovered from the modifications they made to the code.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Prompt students to recall the attributes of the `Painter` class. Ask students how they think the no-argument constructor for the `Painter` class might have been written based on what they remember about how a `Painter` object was instantiated.\n\nPoint out that the class has methods to get the current values assigned to the instance variables. Students will learn more about the syntax and functionality of these methods in a later lesson, but you can ask students how these methods are similar to the `getX()`, `getY()`, `getDirection()`, and `getMyPaint()` methods in the `Painter` class that allowed them to get the current values assigned to the instance variables for a `Painter` object."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4701a439-dcbb-405b-a3c1-51a4cc4ef999",
        "lesson_activity.key": "78bdc6b5-598a-4639-923d-2f57eea8b56d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a77d8ff9-695d-4028-96ab-7213ccf73c3b",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Show the video – *Constructors*.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Videos are used throughout the curriculum to spark discussions, supplement key concepts with additional explanations and examples, and expose students to the various roles and backgrounds of individuals in computer science.\n\nWhile interacting with the video, turn on closed captioning so students can also read along as they watch.\n\nTo encourage active engagement and reflection, use one or more of the strategies discussed in the [**Guide to Curriculum Videos**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1FqIUpJg6MrgdtbFGLobSojOz0u1m5Jge1nMAjUqI5ZM/edit?usp=sharing)."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a77d8ff9-695d-4028-96ab-7213ccf73c3b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "78bdc6b5-598a-4639-923d-2f57eea8b56d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a66e70b1-8ea3-4c51-8437-4ef0bd362d50",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Do This:** Explain the components of a constructor:\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> The access modifier\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> The name of the constructor is the same as the class\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Empty parentheses since there are no parameters\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Define ***constructor signature***\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Assign values to the instance variables\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 5 on Code Studio to practice writing a no-argument constructor in a class.",
        "progression_name": "Skill Building: Writing a Constructor"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a66e70b1-8ea3-4c51-8437-4ef0bd362d50",
        "lesson_activity.key": "78bdc6b5-598a-4639-923d-2f57eea8b56d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3be504af-1a2b-4afe-b546-7101f55f16f0",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***default value***.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to explain that if a no-argument constructor is not written in the class, Java will automatically provide one and assign the default values for the data type.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If students run the tests on the level before writing a no-argument constructor, they may have noticed that the test for the no-argument constructor initially passes. Point this out to students to reinforce this and to note the need to confirm test results if when the test passes."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3be504af-1a2b-4afe-b546-7101f55f16f0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "78bdc6b5-598a-4639-923d-2f57eea8b56d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ffa41af4-a773-4ea1-9b4e-67b300654bf6",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How should we decide what the default values should be for an object's instance variables?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students share suggestions for making these decisions and may share examples to support their suggestions. Students should realize that they should establish values for what they would consider a \"default object\" if the user does not specify values, such as the `Painter` object starting at (0, 0) or a new profile page on a social media app starting with a default profile image.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Hold That Thought strategy to allow students to write down their thoughts on paper first. Emphasize that they do not need to write complete sentences – they can write a few words, bullet points, draw a quick sketch, or anything else that will help them gather and recall their thoughts when it is time to share with the class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ffa41af4-a773-4ea1-9b4e-67b300654bf6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "78bdc6b5-598a-4639-923d-2f57eea8b56d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "685fe430-7965-40f9-9cc0-0f6e2e66c61d",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What was useful about the no-argument constructor in the `Painter` class? What was NOT useful about it?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students suggest that creating `Painter` objects with the no-argument constructor meant that they always knew where the object was going to start, what direction it would be facing, and that it had no paint. Students may make connections with achieving consistency and reliability in their programs since they could trust that an object would always be created the same way. They share how a different approach would have been more useful if they wanted the `Painter` object to start at a specific location or with a certain amount of paint.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "No-Argument Constructors",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "You do not need to mention parameterized constructors here since students will learn about these in the next lesson. The goal is to get them to start considering the possibility or need for a different type of constructor to help identify when they would want to use one over the other."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "685fe430-7965-40f9-9cc0-0f6e2e66c61d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "78bdc6b5-598a-4639-923d-2f57eea8b56d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c8a6a8c1-8d07-4706-8828-dda9df91eade",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 6 on Code Studio to complete Levels 6, 7, and 8. Students complete a Check for Understanding on Level 6, then continue to Level 7 to write a new class with instance variables and a no-argument constructor. On Level 8, students write a no-argument constructor in the `Dessert` class.",
        "progression_name": "Practice: Writing a Class"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c8a6a8c1-8d07-4706-8828-dda9df91eade",
        "lesson_activity.key": "78bdc6b5-598a-4639-923d-2f57eea8b56d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "70b0726e-7aac-4f7a-a55f-df6a53acf5cf",
      "position": 13,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Practice: The Food Truck",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Check for Understanding and practice level can be used as a formative assessment to gauge understanding of the key terms and writing no-argument constructors in a class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "70b0726e-7aac-4f7a-a55f-df6a53acf5cf",
        "lesson_activity.key": "78bdc6b5-598a-4639-923d-2f57eea8b56d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f64205df-9559-48da-856a-4144b87d3857",
      "position": 14,
      "properties": {
        "description": "This is a good time to commit our code and save our `Dessert` class to the Backpack. We will be adding to the classes throughout the unit as we learn more about designing classes and their components.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f64205df-9559-48da-856a-4144b87d3857",
        "lesson_activity.key": "78bdc6b5-598a-4639-923d-2f57eea8b56d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2ffd1dff-5201-42ba-9f50-e514f6f67732",
      "position": 15,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Play the music clip to cue committing their code and saving their `Dessert` class to the Backpack.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Using music to cue transitions helps create routines in the classroom. When students hear cues, they know it is time to transition to a specific activity. Emphasize to students what the music clip means, and be consistent with the use of the music clip to cue the activity.\n\nClick the blue play icon on the slide to play the music cue."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2ffd1dff-5201-42ba-9f50-e514f6f67732",
        "lesson_activity.key": "78bdc6b5-598a-4639-923d-2f57eea8b56d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9ebb8918-28a4-425f-be01-90bf9eea3983",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We now know how to create several key components of a class – instance variables, constructors, and methods. With these, we are able to define what attributes and behaviors an object should have and provide instructions for how an object should be instantiated.",
        "name": "Question Stems",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9ebb8918-28a4-425f-be01-90bf9eea3983",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e06a5d75-51f9-4311-9170-3ccef081ac8d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "49607b4a-a530-46a0-9900-c635d00e466a",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student an index card or piece of scrap paper.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to write a question on their index card using one of the question stems. Have students turn to a neighbor and take turns asking and answering their questions.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the concepts covered in this lesson.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Question of the Day.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Key Vocabulary"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "49607b4a-a530-46a0-9900-c635d00e466a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e06a5d75-51f9-4311-9170-3ccef081ac8d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1fec6334-3880-4ad5-ade7-9e24a7823702",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "---"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1fec6334-3880-4ad5-ade7-9e24a7823702",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e06a5d75-51f9-4311-9170-3ccef081ac8d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3090c847-51b6-4349-bc0e-3254a921beba",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "*Check For Understanding Question(s) and solutions can be found in each lesson on Code Studio. These questions can be used for an exit ticket.*",
        "name": "Assessment: Check for Understanding",
        "progression_name": "Check for Understanding"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3090c847-51b6-4349-bc0e-3254a921beba",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e06a5d75-51f9-4311-9170-3ccef081ac8d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9719c733-4c9f-4a07-952a-6d311449cdb3",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "When we created a `Painter` object, it always started at the same location with no paint and facing the same direction. The constructor we used set default values for its attributes.",
        "name": "Revisiting the Painter Class",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9719c733-4c9f-4a07-952a-6d311449cdb3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "034d9ad8-854c-4290-8418-ff962fdee901"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "46c9692b-66ad-449f-b7c8-8419fcc8adbc",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What did you wish you could do when creating a `Painter` object?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students recall that the `Painter` class constructor created a `Painter` object at the top-left corner of The Neighborhood with no paint facing east. Students suggest creating a `Painter` object at a specific location with a starting amount of paint and facing a specified direction.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Retrieve-Pair-Share strategy to facilitate this discussion by directing students to write down their thoughts and ideas first, then pair up students to compare their answers and expand their notes. This allows time for individual processing and idea generation before sharing thoughts with others. Ask students to share the ideas they discussed with their partners as a class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "46c9692b-66ad-449f-b7c8-8419fcc8adbc",
        "lesson_activity.key": "034d9ad8-854c-4290-8418-ff962fdee901"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2b435c72-6415-4b91-856a-7440325ded2b",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Introduction"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2b435c72-6415-4b91-856a-7440325ded2b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a5bb1b64-2b23-4788-802f-d167ff453775"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "283e9b65-f1ee-466e-8327-c999c0ad8b72",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We now know how to declare instance variables in a class to represent the attributes of an object and how to write a no-argument constructor to assign default values to these instance variables. Sometimes, though, we want to provide specific values for the instance variables when we instantiate an object. Today, we're going to find out how we can do this.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "283e9b65-f1ee-466e-8327-c999c0ad8b72",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a5bb1b64-2b23-4788-802f-d167ff453775"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "299db32c-0425-4a82-82ac-c622be18a5e5",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 1 on Code Studio to predict the program's outcome, then run the program to compare their predictions to the actual outcome.",
        "progression_name": "Predict and Run: Parameterized Constructors"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "299db32c-0425-4a82-82ac-c622be18a5e5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a5bb1b64-2b23-4788-802f-d167ff453775"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "937f86a3-b984-4ae1-b202-eee5999e50cd",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What did you notice about the code in this program?*\n* *What do you wonder about the code in this program?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students notice that the class has a constructor that has variables inside the parentheses and that these variables are used to assign values to the instance variables. They also notice that the object that is instantiated with specific values now has those values assigned to its instance variables, while the object that is instantiated with the no-argument constructor has the default values assigned to its instance variables. Students may wonder about the syntax and functionality of the additional constructor, whether there is a limit to how many constructors they can have in a class, or when they might use one constructor over another."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "937f86a3-b984-4ae1-b202-eee5999e50cd",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a5bb1b64-2b23-4788-802f-d167ff453775"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8ae675f8-ae23-437e-bd6e-fc06213ed1d6",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***state*** and explain that when a constructor is called, it sets the state of the object by assigning the values to the instance variables.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Parameterized Constructors",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Prompt students to recall the state of a `Painter` object when it is instantiated. Ask students about the instance variables of the `Painter` class and what values were assigned to the instance variables when they instantiated a `Painter` object."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8ae675f8-ae23-437e-bd6e-fc06213ed1d6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a5bb1b64-2b23-4788-802f-d167ff453775"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2d4f8573-d964-4a58-8f1c-a24b16cb9173",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What are some limitations of a no-argument constructor?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students suggest that a no-argument constructor limits the objects they can create because all objects start with the default values for its instance variables. Students may share examples, such as instantiating a `Painter` object with the no-argument constructor and then needing to navigate to a starting position to paint a mural.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 2 on Code Studio to complete Levels 2, 3, and 4. Students investigate the program, make changes to the program as prompted, and observe the results.",
        "progression_name": "Investigate and Modify: Parameterized Constructors"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2d4f8573-d964-4a58-8f1c-a24b16cb9173",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a5bb1b64-2b23-4788-802f-d167ff453775"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "42b32102-4590-4968-9ef1-761c9794eca6",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students share what they discovered from the modifications they made to the code."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "42b32102-4590-4968-9ef1-761c9794eca6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a5bb1b64-2b23-4788-802f-d167ff453775"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "bfbc04ff-670c-40ef-b6b1-0f958c5fa6e5",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***parameterized constructor*** and introduce the parameterized constructor in the `Painter` class.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***overloading***.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Show the video – *Overloaded Constructors*.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Writing and Using Constructors",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Videos are used throughout the curriculum to spark discussions, supplement key concepts with additional explanations and examples, and expose students to the various roles and backgrounds of individuals in computer science.\n\nWhile interacting with the video, turn on closed captioning so students can also read along as they watch.\n\nTo encourage active engagement and reflection, use one or more of the strategies discussed in the [**Guide to Curriculum Videos**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1FqIUpJg6MrgdtbFGLobSojOz0u1m5Jge1nMAjUqI5ZM/edit?usp=sharing)."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "bfbc04ff-670c-40ef-b6b1-0f958c5fa6e5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a5bb1b64-2b23-4788-802f-d167ff453775"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a29f07fc-37f2-4b4b-abb7-8e4c588d70d4",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What are the similarities and differences between a no-argument constructor and a parameterized constructor?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students note that both constructors set the starting values for the instance variables when an object is instantiated. They note that these are different because the no-argument constructor sets default values for the instance variables, while the parameterized constructor sets user-specified values.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Retrieve-Pair-Share strategy to facilitate this discussion by directing students to write down their thoughts and ideas first, then pair up students to compare their answers and expand their notes. This allows time for individual processing and idea generation before sharing thoughts with others. Ask students to share the ideas they discussed with their partners as a class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a29f07fc-37f2-4b4b-abb7-8e4c588d70d4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a5bb1b64-2b23-4788-802f-d167ff453775"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2fbb1a92-1845-4597-a93e-d9b92e873af0",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *When do you think it's best to use a no-argument constructor? What about a parameterized constructor?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students suggest using a no-argument constructor when a default object is needed because the user has not given specific values. They note that a parameterized constructor is best when the user needs an object to be instantiated with specific starting values.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Have students recall problems from the previous unit that could have been easier if they started at a specific location or with a certain amount of paint. Ask students to consider their Asphalt Art Project and how starting with a certain amount of paint or at a specific location might have impacted their project."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2fbb1a92-1845-4597-a93e-d9b92e873af0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a5bb1b64-2b23-4788-802f-d167ff453775"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "217afc20-a1b4-487a-b4f0-85b62a18f15a",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Do This:** Explain the components of a parameterized constructor:\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Define ***formal parameter***\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Define ***local variable***\n\n**Do This:** Explain how parameterized constructors are called:\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Define ***actual parameter***\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Click through the animated slide to demonstrate ***call by value***\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 5 on Code Studio to complete Levels 5, 6, and 7. Students complete a Check for Understanding on Level 5, then continue to Level 6 to practice writing a parameterized constructor in a class. On Level 7, students practice writing multiple parameterized constructors in a class.",
        "progression_name": "Practice: Parameterized Constructors"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "217afc20-a1b4-487a-b4f0-85b62a18f15a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a5bb1b64-2b23-4788-802f-d167ff453775"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5cd5ba49-50ce-4b98-8701-6b4792719aa8",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What did we learn today?*\n* *So what?*\n* *Now what?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students highlight the concepts and vocabulary they learned in this lesson, such as parameterized constructor, formal parameter, and actual parameter. Students also recall that formal parameters are local variables and explain how the values of the actual parameters are copied to the formal parameters. They should realize that parameterized constructors can provide multiple options for instantiating objects based on the needs of the program.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the concepts covered in this lesson.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Question of the Day.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Key Vocabulary",
        "name": "Three W's"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5cd5ba49-50ce-4b98-8701-6b4792719aa8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "231f209e-d73e-4370-975a-32f148713d4d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3dab096a-e6b6-4e7e-ba79-6f8f136d570c",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "---"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3dab096a-e6b6-4e7e-ba79-6f8f136d570c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "231f209e-d73e-4370-975a-32f148713d4d"
      }
