    {
      "key": "dcaff571-b649-4992-beab-d2408b33264e",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We interact with software every day. Most of the apps and systems we use get input from us to perform the tasks they are programmed to complete.",
        "name": "Input Methods",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "dcaff571-b649-4992-beab-d2408b33264e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b6ecb6df-f5bb-4eb2-937c-3b719e1a9fb1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e98c40aa-55ac-4cd0-bfbe-db65620bcf7f",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain the program examples and their methods of input.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts. \n- *What are some apps and systems that you use every day?*\n- *What types of inputs do these apps and systems use?*\n- *How do they get these inputs from the user?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students identify apps and systems they use on mobile devices, gaming consoles, or computers. Students share inputs that these apps and systems use, such as entering personal information, moving a character in a game, or entering content in a document. Students discuss how they enter input to apps and systems, including touchscreen input and button selections.\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Ask students about specific apps they use on their mobile devices or programs for school work. Have students consider the types of inputs for these apps and programs.\n\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e98c40aa-55ac-4cd0-bfbe-db65620bcf7f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b6ecb6df-f5bb-4eb2-937c-3b719e1a9fb1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "54eb83f2-3418-4c88-9c92-116d0c49caa0",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Getting input from a user is an important aspect of many apps and programs we use every day. User input makes a program more interactive and adaptable to individual needs and information.\n\n",
        "name": "The Scanner Class",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "54eb83f2-3418-4c88-9c92-116d0c49caa0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "80216add-2623-4a2f-819b-21277e01f090"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "039bbc88-a3b5-4ebc-92a2-32be3bab33d8",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***application program interface (API)*** and ***library***.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the `java.util` package and the `Scanner` class.\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "The term package was introduced in Unit 1 when The Neighborhood was introduced. Ask students to recall the meaning of package and how The Neighborhood consists of classes that can be imported and used."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "039bbc88-a3b5-4ebc-92a2-32be3bab33d8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "80216add-2623-4a2f-819b-21277e01f090"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "003f93d3-d23f-4553-8710-bd7db5c31ad4",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Show the video – *Creating a Scanner Object*.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 1 on Code Studio to predict the program's outcome, then run the program to compare their predictions to the actual outcome.\n",
        "progression_name": "Predict: Getting User Input"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "003f93d3-d23f-4553-8710-bd7db5c31ad4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "80216add-2623-4a2f-819b-21277e01f090"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "feff144e-036a-4da8-ae32-8dfd96101fb0",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n- *What do you notice about the code in this program?*\n- *What do you wonder about the code in this program?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students notice that a user can input values into the program. Students may wonder what other methods are in the `Scanner` class for getting user input."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "feff144e-036a-4da8-ae32-8dfd96101fb0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "80216add-2623-4a2f-819b-21277e01f090"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "fdb35cf8-5891-4c1d-a4e8-46054cc9938c",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "The `Scanner` class has several methods for obtaining input based on the type of data we want to get from the user. Let's look at some of the methods that we will use today.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "fdb35cf8-5891-4c1d-a4e8-46054cc9938c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "80216add-2623-4a2f-819b-21277e01f090"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f82d9732-ec7f-4e00-8c14-856e1aa5cf7f",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Show the video – *Scanner Class Methods*.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What are some ways you could use these methods in your programs?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students suggest types of information they could obtain from a user, such as asking how much paint a `Painter` object should start with or a flavor for a `Dessert` object.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Ask students to consider how they might use input to decide the starting values for Painter or Dessert objects or perform calculations."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f82d9732-ec7f-4e00-8c14-856e1aa5cf7f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "80216add-2623-4a2f-819b-21277e01f090"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "49da729d-85fd-40fd-ab74-cd236bf5a1f3",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to demonstrate common errors using `Scanner` class methods.\n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "49da729d-85fd-40fd-ab74-cd236bf5a1f3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "80216add-2623-4a2f-819b-21277e01f090"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9cbc51fa-92b1-43e9-8503-3de3731c12f3",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "The methods we saw in the video earlier are not the only methods available in the `Scanner` class. We can refer to the documentation for the `Scanner` class to see what methods it has and how to use them.\n\n",
        "name": "Getting User Input",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9cbc51fa-92b1-43e9-8503-3de3731c12f3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "80216add-2623-4a2f-819b-21277e01f090"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "05b1e99e-a437-4011-876c-4ec7c706f049",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to demonstrate how to access documentation in Java Lab.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 2 to complete a choice level to create and use a `Scanner` object to obtain user input.",
        "progression_name": "Practice: Getting User Input"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
