    {
      "key": "b894a494-1641-4e0a-ae78-afb86c6a7256",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to recall how subclasses inherit the attributes and methods of the superclass and explain that constructors are not inherited.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *If a subclass inherits instance variables from the superclass but not its constructor, what problems might happen when we try to create a subclass object?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students recognize that constructors are used to initialize instance variables. Without inheriting constructors, they may reason that subclass objects could be created without necessary values, leading to incorrect or incomplete objects. Some students might suggest that the subclass would need its own way to pass values to the superclass.",
        "name": "Revisiting Inheritance",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Hold That Thought strategy to allow students to write down their thoughts on paper first. Emphasize that they do not need to write complete sentences – they can write a few words, bullet points, draw a quick sketch, or anything else that will help them gather and recall their thoughts when it is time to share with the class.\n\nStudents might suggest making the instance variables in the superclass `public` instead of `private` so that the subclass can access them. Prompt students to recall why instance variables should be `private` and ask students to consider ways they could pass information from the subclass to the superclass based on what they have learned about Java so far."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b894a494-1641-4e0a-ae78-afb86c6a7256",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d7e473a5-adc3-4d1a-ae2a-49764b74c03d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9b1158ec-ccdc-469e-8633-6cd1edde9a96",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Introduction"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9b1158ec-ccdc-469e-8633-6cd1edde9a96",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e9524ead-7fc7-46fe-83dd-c2119100cd1a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a2f7dba5-a29f-45a4-95d4-641463cd4b29",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We have seen how we can instantiate objects with no-argument and parameterized constructors and use the `this` keyword to minimize redundancies in a class. In the previous unit, we used inheritance to create subclasses that share the attributes and behaviors of a superclass. Today, we're going to explore how we can write constructors to assign values to the attributes that are declared in a superclass.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a2f7dba5-a29f-45a4-95d4-641463cd4b29",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e9524ead-7fc7-46fe-83dd-c2119100cd1a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "aab9f70c-d6aa-4f10-9ff6-8768acd02523",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 1 on Code Studio to predict the program's outcome, then run the program to compare their predictions to the actual outcome.",
        "progression_name": "Predict and Run: Constructors and Inheritance"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "aab9f70c-d6aa-4f10-9ff6-8768acd02523",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e9524ead-7fc7-46fe-83dd-c2119100cd1a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0152a2d2-5119-40fa-9252-1847a0775782",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What did you notice about the code in this program?*\n* *What do you wonder about the code in this program?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students notice that the constructor in the subclass uses the keyword `super` to pass the values of the parameters to the superclass constructor. Students might also identify some similarities between the `super` keyword and the `this` keyword. Students may wonder if the `super` keyword works similarly to the `this` keyword or what might happen if they do not use the `super` keyword in a subclass constructor."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0152a2d2-5119-40fa-9252-1847a0775782",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e9524ead-7fc7-46fe-83dd-c2119100cd1a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c4118975-d04b-44f9-8545-b0750a1f1c1e",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Recall that superclasses inherit the instance variables of a superclass and explain that superclasses cannot access them because they are `private`.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 2 on Code Studio to complete Levels 2, 3, and 4. Students investigate the program, make changes to the program as prompted, and observe the results.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Calling the Superclass Constructor",
        "progression_name": "Investigate and Modify: The super Keyword"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c4118975-d04b-44f9-8545-b0750a1f1c1e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e9524ead-7fc7-46fe-83dd-c2119100cd1a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f0cfda9e-450e-4c2d-8a01-f5fff0753fc1",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students share what they discovered from the modifications they made to the code.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Ask students to share what happened when the subclass constructor did not call the superclass constructor or when the call to superclass constructor was not the first line in the body. Have students suggest why they think this happened and what they might conclude based on their findings."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f0cfda9e-450e-4c2d-8a01-f5fff0753fc1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e9524ead-7fc7-46fe-83dd-c2119100cd1a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "08320b85-2a55-4d7f-8a52-c3d9ed5efea2",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the `super` keyword and explain how it is used to call the superclass constructor.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to explain that when a subclass constructor does not explicitly call a superclass constructor using `super`, Java inserts a call to the superclass no-argument constructor.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the `Object` class.\n\n**Do This:** Demonstrate the process of calling superclass constructors:\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> The process continues until the `Object` constructor is called\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> All constructors in the hierarchy execute beginning with the `Object` constructor"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "08320b85-2a55-4d7f-8a52-c3d9ed5efea2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e9524ead-7fc7-46fe-83dd-c2119100cd1a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1183ddc9-09ce-4b47-9b27-46efa8067ba6",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We now have all the tools we need to write no-argument and parameterized constructors in a class and in subclasses. Let's practice putting all of these concepts together!",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Putting It All Together",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1183ddc9-09ce-4b47-9b27-46efa8067ba6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e9524ead-7fc7-46fe-83dd-c2119100cd1a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "edd97f0e-d82b-4070-926f-7363c38c6178",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 5 on Code Studio to complete Levels 5, 6, and 7. On Level 5, students complete a Check for Understanding, then continue to Level 6 to write a parameterized constructor in a subclass using the `super` keyword. On Level 7, students write no-argument and parameterized constructors in their `Dessert` subclass.",
        "progression_name": "Practice: The super Keyword",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Check for Understanding and practice level can be used as a formative assessment to gauge understanding of the key terms and using the `super` keyword with parameterized constructors in a class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "edd97f0e-d82b-4070-926f-7363c38c6178",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e9524ead-7fc7-46fe-83dd-c2119100cd1a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "781520d0-96d9-474a-889e-6279b77dfa75",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "This is a good time to commit our code and save our `Dessert` subclass to the Backpack. We will be adding to the classes throughout the unit as we learn more about designing classes and their components.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "781520d0-96d9-474a-889e-6279b77dfa75",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e9524ead-7fc7-46fe-83dd-c2119100cd1a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a2f92f5b-d33c-4d2a-b2e1-d84e4c25e569",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Play the music clip to cue committing their code and saving their `Dessert` subclass to the Backpack.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Using music to cue transitions helps create routines in the classroom. When students hear cues, they know it is time to transition to a specific activity. Emphasize to students what the music clip means, and be consistent with the use of the music clip to cue the activity.\n\nClick the blue play icon on the slide to play the music cue."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a2f92f5b-d33c-4d2a-b2e1-d84e4c25e569",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e9524ead-7fc7-46fe-83dd-c2119100cd1a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5a2e72b0-e965-42ff-878e-f4b2998d6f12",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Do This: Designate four corners or areas in the classroom for each possible explanation of why we use `super()` in a subclass constructor. Have students go to the corner they believe is correct.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Do This: Once in their corners, have students work together to justify their choice. Encourage them to prepare a short explanation of why their answer is correct — or why other options are incorrect — and share out with the class.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the concepts covered in this lesson.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Question of the Day.",
        "name": "Constructor Corners"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5a2e72b0-e965-42ff-878e-f4b2998d6f12",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ba6aafbe-0ee2-4601-ae4c-2117bba45c55"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d4b5ae9c-10e7-4bed-b0c0-1b598f652324",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "---"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d4b5ae9c-10e7-4bed-b0c0-1b598f652324",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ba6aafbe-0ee2-4601-ae4c-2117bba45c55"
      }
