      }
    },
    {
      "key": "be7dd9ef-fe94-4d19-b0cf-df6009e943fa",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We have learned a lot of new terms so far! Let's review some of these terms through a game of CS Pyramid.",
        "name": "CS Pyramid",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "be7dd9ef-fe94-4d19-b0cf-df6009e943fa",
        "lesson_activity.key": "cbf731c6-5db2-4927-9104-005c8897d39f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "90248592-f57f-4a4c-af57-c3a060543751",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Group:** Place students in pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the instructions for playing CS Pyramid.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Play the music clip to cue the CS Pyramid activity, and direct students to play the first round of CS Pyramid.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Play the music clip to cue the CS Pyramid activity, and direct students to switch roles to play the second round of CS Pyramid.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "The CS Pyramid activity is based on the 10,000 Pyramid game. Check out the [**Teacher Toolkit: 10,000 Pyramid (High School)**](https://youtu.be/ZOUS34gDHoM) video for a preview of how this activity is run."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "90248592-f57f-4a4c-af57-c3a060543751",
        "lesson_activity.key": "cbf731c6-5db2-4927-9104-005c8897d39f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a742bef7-79df-4e8d-9919-27d8b4e9081a",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Introduction"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a742bef7-79df-4e8d-9919-27d8b4e9081a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fa36fb81-76fd-4001-850b-87622b5cedea"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2d90a73f-3a83-44b4-b1db-61d54339758d",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We have used variables to hold information about a `Painter` object, such as its current x and y location and how much paint it had. We have also represented the attributes of an object as instance variables in a class. Today, we will take a closer look at the different types of variables and how we can work with them in our programs.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2d90a73f-3a83-44b4-b1db-61d54339758d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fa36fb81-76fd-4001-850b-87622b5cedea"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7c816e03-fce4-4a0b-96eb-e1ed596ecd19",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 1 on Code Studio to predict the program's outcome, then run the program to compare their predictions to the actual outcome.",
        "progression_name": "Predict and Run: Variables"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7c816e03-fce4-4a0b-96eb-e1ed596ecd19",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fa36fb81-76fd-4001-850b-87622b5cedea"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "be5a87e8-691c-4ba6-bcf1-5f25cf364e55",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What did you notice about the code in this program?*\n* *What do you wonder about the code in this program?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students notice the different types of values and how a `String` can be created. Students also notice that the ending values of a variable can be different from the value the variable is created with. Students may wonder if there are other data types or why a `String` can be created in different ways."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "be5a87e8-691c-4ba6-bcf1-5f25cf364e55",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fa36fb81-76fd-4001-850b-87622b5cedea"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7cc434df-bd11-4c4c-b6f8-defb8d6ab3da",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Recall variables and data types.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student a copy of the Investigate: Variables handout.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 2 on Code Studio. Students investigate the program and complete the Investigate: Variables handout.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Exploring Variables",
        "progression_name": "Investigate and Modify: Variables"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7cc434df-bd11-4c4c-b6f8-defb8d6ab3da",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fa36fb81-76fd-4001-850b-87622b5cedea"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6db0bb90-a8b5-4f4d-879e-20601fef8751",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students share what they discovered from the modifications they made to the code and their responses on the Investigate: Variables handout.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Ask students what they noticed about creating a `String` and why they think this is different from creating variables for `int`, `double`, or `boolean` values."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6db0bb90-a8b5-4f4d-879e-20601fef8751",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fa36fb81-76fd-4001-850b-87622b5cedea"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "dae430e7-8e40-4903-b008-24e2c25aba28",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We have now seen different ways we can create and work with variables in a program. Let's take a look at the different components involved in creating and working with variables in Java.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Primitive and Reference Variables",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "dae430e7-8e40-4903-b008-24e2c25aba28",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fa36fb81-76fd-4001-850b-87622b5cedea"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4a397acf-8c42-4b29-abd6-4e51b81d5139",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Show the video – *Creating Variables*.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Videos are used throughout the curriculum to spark discussions, supplement key concepts with additional explanations and examples, and expose students to the various roles and backgrounds of individuals in computer science.\n\nWhile interacting with the video, turn on closed captioning so students can also read along as they watch.\n\nTo encourage active engagement and reflection, use one or more of the strategies discussed in the [**Guide to Curriculum Videos**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1FqIUpJg6MrgdtbFGLobSojOz0u1m5Jge1nMAjUqI5ZM/edit?usp=sharing)."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4a397acf-8c42-4b29-abd6-4e51b81d5139",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fa36fb81-76fd-4001-850b-87622b5cedea"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "de642f16-67f3-4dfb-9c65-08dd42b97545",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Do This:** Explain how to declare and initialize a variable:\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Recall declaring a variable\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Define ***assignment*** and introduce the assignment operator ( `=` )\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Define ***initialization***\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Define ***literal***",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Point out to students that the assignment operator assigns the value on the right to the variable on the left. Read the assignment operator as \"gets\" rather than \"equals\" to emphasize this and prompt students to consider how the operator works differently in Java than in scenarios like math equations."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "de642f16-67f3-4dfb-9c65-08dd42b97545",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fa36fb81-76fd-4001-850b-87622b5cedea"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e2c9acd5-0726-47b8-91cd-4ff3d7f677e1",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***primitive type***.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***reference type***.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *When have we used primitive variables in our programs? What about reference variables?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students recall using primitive variables to store the current x and y location and amount of paint for a `Painter` object and to represent the price of a `Dessert` object. Students recall using reference variables for objects they have created so far, such as `Painter` and `Dessert` objects.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Retrieve-Pair-Share strategy to facilitate this discussion by directing students to write down their thoughts and ideas first, then pair up students to compare their answers and expand their notes. This allows time for individual processing and idea generation before sharing thoughts with others. Ask students to share the ideas they discussed with their partners as a class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e2c9acd5-0726-47b8-91cd-4ff3d7f677e1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fa36fb81-76fd-4001-850b-87622b5cedea"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "824cb6cf-7699-4332-8116-c27c3aa6becb",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that a `String` is an object, or an instance of the `String` class.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to introduce the `String` class and demonstrate creating `String` objects using the `new` keyword.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to demonstrate tracing the code segment to identify the current values stored in each variable.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students trace the code segment to identify the current values stored in each variable.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the solution as a class."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "824cb6cf-7699-4332-8116-c27c3aa6becb",
