    {
      "key": "714a5189-ca52-4f52-be5b-96a989d141fd",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "There are many examples in software engineering of real-world consequences for a computer’s storage limitations. Let’s watch a short clip and see an example of one situation where the consequences cost hundreds of millions of dollars..",
        "name": "Overflow Errors",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "714a5189-ca52-4f52-be5b-96a989d141fd",
        "lesson_activity.key": "48e741ea-46d5-43fa-a659-bf0a06ac26b9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a24b3c22-0e52-458c-a253-f8ccc1ca7747",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Show the video – Ariane 5 rocket launch explosion.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "The first two minutes of the video are a valuable support for the warm-up discussion. Teachers may choose to show the entire five minute video, but it is not necessary for the discussion to be productive.\n\n\nTo encourage active engagement and reflection, use one or more of the strategies discussed in the [**Guide to Curriculum Videos**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1FqIUpJg6MrgdtbFGLobSojOz0u1m5Jge1nMAjUqI5ZM/edit?usp=sharing)."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a24b3c22-0e52-458c-a253-f8ccc1ca7747",
        "lesson_activity.key": "48e741ea-46d5-43fa-a659-bf0a06ac26b9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c6a7f050-5cc4-463a-841c-d1451f99d53c",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c6a7f050-5cc4-463a-841c-d1451f99d53c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "48e741ea-46d5-43fa-a659-bf0a06ac26b9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6a456375-f6cc-4741-8b23-6a9267b8255c",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:**  *What other situations involving very large numbers might be impacted by overflow errors?.*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students should recognize that there is a maximum value that computers can hold. They might point to examples like Gangnam Style overflowing YouTube, an odometer overflowing, or Y2K.."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6a456375-f6cc-4741-8b23-6a9267b8255c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "48e741ea-46d5-43fa-a659-bf0a06ac26b9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "86d955c1-dda3-4bb8-990b-b3b6bee7d3a1",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Introduction"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "86d955c1-dda3-4bb8-990b-b3b6bee7d3a1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "85b6d324-353a-423e-b139-1f7a034bf6bc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c37ceb16-7fdc-47d4-ac24-c3f9f8d266b5",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We have seen an example of the consequences of overflow errors. Now let’s take a look at some of the ways to anticipate overflow errors in Java.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c37ceb16-7fdc-47d4-ac24-c3f9f8d266b5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "85b6d324-353a-423e-b139-1f7a034bf6bc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5438323c-6d43-4f4e-a011-304be743885d",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 1 on Code Studio to predict the program's outcome, then run the program to compare their predictions to the actual outcome.",
        "progression_name": "Predict and Run: Overflow Errors"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5438323c-6d43-4f4e-a011-304be743885d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "85b6d324-353a-423e-b139-1f7a034bf6bc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "13bd371b-584f-4a73-9676-23fb0fa16d07",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts\n\n* *What did you notice about the code in this program?*\n* *What do you wonder about the code in this program?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students notice that in the overflow example, the value becomes negative, and in the underflow example, the negative value becomes positive. Students may wonder about how the Integer class works and how to avoid overflow errors. "
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "13bd371b-584f-4a73-9676-23fb0fa16d07",
        "lesson_activity.key": "85b6d324-353a-423e-b139-1f7a034bf6bc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "75f5a5ab-4ddd-4d36-84cc-02a2667ae401",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "The `Integer` and `Double` classes are known as wrapper classes. Java provides a wrapper class for each primitive type, which also gives us access to constants we can use for `int` and `double` values. We will learn much more about wrapper classes later in the course.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Exploring Overflow and Roundoff",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "75f5a5ab-4ddd-4d36-84cc-02a2667ae401",
        "lesson_activity.key": "85b6d324-353a-423e-b139-1f7a034bf6bc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "37981064-18dd-4547-b92f-7a105f146353",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Click through the animated slide to introduce the `Integer` and `Double` classes and their constants.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 2 on Code Studio complete Levels 2 and 3. Students investigate the program, make changes to the program as prompted, and observe the results.",
        "progression_name": "Investigate and Modify: Roundoff Errors"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "37981064-18dd-4547-b92f-7a105f146353",
        "lesson_activity.key": "85b6d324-353a-423e-b139-1f7a034bf6bc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b6867a3e-32c9-4ec1-8413-6aa4d1553657",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students share what they discovered from the modifications they made to the code.\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students should notice a different behavior from exceeding the maximum value of `Double` objects.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain the minimum and maximum values for integers:\n* Integers in Java have 32 bits of space\n* `Integer.MIN_VALUE`\n* `Integer.MAX_VALUE`\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to define **overflow**.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to define **underflow**.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain the connection between doubles and **round-off errors.**"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b6867a3e-32c9-4ec1-8413-6aa4d1553657",
        "lesson_activity.key": "85b6d324-353a-423e-b139-1f7a034bf6bc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7d8e21c0-9c3d-4068-839b-3433b909337c",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "As we saw in the discussion we had during the warm up, overflow errors do have consequences in many situations. By recognizing the possibility of a round-off error occurring, software engineers can design programs that anticipate and prevent roundoff errors. ",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Practice: Handling Overflow ",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7d8e21c0-9c3d-4068-839b-3433b909337c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "85b6d324-353a-423e-b139-1f7a034bf6bc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "86837745-54ad-4742-b319-b7bc69ab3708",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 4 on Code Studio to complete Levels 4 and 5. Students complete a Check for Understanding, then continue to complete a choice level on Level 5 to practice anticipating and working around potential overflow errors.",
        "progression_name": "Practice: Handling Overflow"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "86837745-54ad-4742-b319-b7bc69ab3708",
        "lesson_activity.key": "85b6d324-353a-423e-b139-1f7a034bf6bc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d3955c98-498c-4243-ab86-901b9d7f9547",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We’ve talked a lot about overflow errors, and had a chance to experiment with overflow errors in our own programs. Now think back to the impact an overflow error had on the Ariane 5 rocket disaster. ",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Avoiding Overflow Errors",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d3955c98-498c-4243-ab86-901b9d7f9547",
        "lesson_activity.key": "55a8e16b-51c8-4226-b011-e752ed4fd332"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5db14e2b-94cf-46da-ade1-50102a64ca60",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Based on what you know now about the range of variables, do you think this was an avoidable error? What could the engineers have done differently?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students may suggest that the error made with the Ariane 5 rocket was avoidable. They could mention a variety of strategies for avoiding overflow errors, such as peer reviewing code, using conditionals, and widening data.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Review the concepts covered in this lesson\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Review the Question of the Day.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Key Vocabulary"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5db14e2b-94cf-46da-ade1-50102a64ca60",
        "lesson_activity.key": "55a8e16b-51c8-4226-b011-e752ed4fd332"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "98e24bc9-7296-4b2d-9299-d92039963005",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We have learned a lot about object-oriented programming and design. Let's take a look at a scenario and see how we might solve this problem.",
        "name": "Design Thinking",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "98e24bc9-7296-4b2d-9299-d92039963005",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9cef8114-6712-4cce-b321-6ea54d3a7e72"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "66070f24-3296-4e42-a3fd-0364726f8513",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *A software engineer is developing a travel app. The user must be able to choose a hotel and a flight for their trip. What classes should the software engineer develop? What attributes and behaviors might each class have?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students suggest creating classes to represent a user, a trip, a hotel, and a flight. They identify attributes for each class, such as the user having a name and a trip and a hotel having a name, a rating, and a price.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "There are multiple ways this scenario could be implemented. Help students identify potential classes by calling out the nouns in the problem statement and asking what attributes and behaviors would be important to how the user should be able to use the app."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "66070f24-3296-4e42-a3fd-0364726f8513",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9cef8114-6712-4cce-b321-6ea54d3a7e72"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3c8f8acc-0d7d-4d0b-9ee1-75e6c3fd09ca",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Introduction"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3c8f8acc-0d7d-4d0b-9ee1-75e6c3fd09ca",
        "lesson_activity.key": "10f18409-a2b1-409d-a152-8391caf6590d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9c3c5dcb-b025-422a-bcef-a907963d5ce7",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "When we want to get information about the state of an object, we have to call each accessor method. If there are multiple instance variables, this can result in multiple lines of code just to get information about an object. What if there was an easier way?",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9c3c5dcb-b025-422a-bcef-a907963d5ce7",
        "lesson_activity.key": "10f18409-a2b1-409d-a152-8391caf6590d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4d8596f7-1b96-4b1f-af8c-09395952fe67",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 1 on Code Studio to predict the program's outcome, then run the program to compare their predictions to the actual outcome.",
        "progression_name": "Predict and Run: Printing Objects"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4d8596f7-1b96-4b1f-af8c-09395952fe67",
        "lesson_activity.key": "10f18409-a2b1-409d-a152-8391caf6590d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4ad30da7-18f4-4454-8280-df88b51e0283",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What did you notice about the code in this program?*\n* *What do you wonder about the code in this program?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students notice that printing an object displays random letters and numbers to the console instead of the values stored in its instance variables. Students may wonder what the letters and numbers mean and why the values are not printed."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4ad30da7-18f4-4454-8280-df88b51e0283",
        "lesson_activity.key": "10f18409-a2b1-409d-a152-8391caf6590d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4ce60829-a4f9-4386-8ce1-e739270dbebe",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Show the video – *The toString() Method*.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Printing Objects",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Videos are used throughout the curriculum to spark discussions, supplement key concepts with additional explanations and examples, and expose students to the various roles and backgrounds of individuals in computer science.\n\nWhile interacting with the video, turn on closed captioning so students can also read along as they watch.\n\nTo encourage active engagement and reflection, use one or more of the strategies discussed in the [**Guide to Curriculum Videos**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1FqIUpJg6MrgdtbFGLobSojOz0u1m5Jge1nMAjUqI5ZM/edit?usp=sharing)."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4ce60829-a4f9-4386-8ce1-e739270dbebe",
        "lesson_activity.key": "10f18409-a2b1-409d-a152-8391caf6590d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6743d9fa-9fdf-48a6-bb6f-aca0da7bda9b",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Do This:** Recall the `Object` class and introduce its `toString()` method:\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> When printing an object, the `toString()` method of the `Object` class is called\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> The `toString()` method returns a `String` consisting of the name of the class, the `@` symbol, and the hash code of the object\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Why do you think the `toString()` method in the `Object` class doesn't print the values stored in the instance variables?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students realize that since the `Object` class is the superclass of all classes, it doesn't know about or have access to the instance variables of any of its subclasses.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Hold That Thought strategy to allow students to write down their thoughts on paper first. Emphasize that they do not need to write complete sentences – they can write a few words, bullet points, draw a quick sketch, or anything else that will help them gather and recall their thoughts when it is time to share with the class.\n\nHelp students make the connection by prompting students to recall the functionality of inheritance. Ask additional guiding questions, such as:\n* *Can a superclass access the attributes or behaviors of a subclass?*"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6743d9fa-9fdf-48a6-bb6f-aca0da7bda9b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "10f18409-a2b1-409d-a152-8391caf6590d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "77e60afb-2738-4f5c-b265-c9a9dec62ca3",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 2 on Code Studio to complete Levels 2 and 3. Students investigate the program, make changes to the program as prompted, and observe the results.",
        "progression_name": "Investigate and Modify: Printing Objects"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "77e60afb-2738-4f5c-b265-c9a9dec62ca3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "10f18409-a2b1-409d-a152-8391caf6590d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "582d7f7c-6ed4-4721-b0ee-48a537d8e272",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students share what they discovered from the modifications they made to the code.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What did you notice about the way the `toString()` method is called?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students realize that the `toString()` method is not explicitly called, but they note that it is used when an object reference is printed.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Hold That Thought strategy to allow students to write down their thoughts on paper first. Emphasize that they do not need to write complete sentences – they can write a few words, bullet points, draw a quick sketch, or anything else that will help them gather and recall their thoughts when it is time to share with the class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "582d7f7c-6ed4-4721-b0ee-48a537d8e272",
        "lesson_activity.key": "10f18409-a2b1-409d-a152-8391caf6590d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "061a3477-ac39-4a2d-823e-66a8bb21b16e",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that the `toString()` method is automatically called when an object reference is passed to a print statement or when an object reference is concatenated with a `String`."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "061a3477-ac39-4a2d-823e-66a8bb21b16e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "10f18409-a2b1-409d-a152-8391caf6590d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "64bdeef0-b779-4c50-966a-0e65013a396e",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "The `toString()` method in the `Object` class isn't very useful when we want to print information about an object. We can write our own version of the `toString()` method so we can print the values stored in the instance variables when we print an object.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "The toString() Method",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "64bdeef0-b779-4c50-966a-0e65013a396e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "10f18409-a2b1-409d-a152-8391caf6590d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1731bdcf-0916-4268-82e9-d1a4f5187018",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***overriding***.\n\n**Do This:** Explain the syntax for overriding the `toString()` method in a class:\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> The method signature is the same as the `toString()` method in the `Object` class\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Return a `String` containing the information about the object\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How could we include the information in the superclass `toString()` method in a subclass `toString()` method?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students suggest calling the superclass `toString()` method in the subclass `toString()` method.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Retrieve-Pair-Share strategy to facilitate this discussion by directing students to write down their thoughts and ideas first, then pair up students to compare their answers and expand their notes. This allows time for individual processing and idea generation before sharing thoughts with others. Ask students to share the ideas they discussed with their partners as a class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1731bdcf-0916-4268-82e9-d1a4f5187018",
        "lesson_activity.key": "10f18409-a2b1-409d-a152-8391caf6590d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "501ae77b-9724-4fbb-99c3-90f21618625f",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that the `super` keyword can be used to call the superclass method.\n\n**Do This:** Introduce escape sequences:\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Define ***escape sequence***\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Printing a quotation mark ( `\\\"` )\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Printing a new line ( `\\n` )\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Printing a backslash ( `\\\\` )\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 4 on Code Studio to complete Levels 4 through 7. Students complete a Check for Understanding on Level 4, then continue to Level 5 to write a `toString()` method in a class. On Level 6, students write a `toString()` method in the `Dessert` class. On Level 7, students write a `toString()` method in the `Dessert` subclass (`Cookie`, `Pie`, `Cupcake`, or `Donut`).",
        "progression_name": "Practice: The toString() Method",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Check for Understanding and practice level can be used as a formative assessment to gauge understanding of the key terms and writing a `toString()` method in a class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "501ae77b-9724-4fbb-99c3-90f21618625f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "10f18409-a2b1-409d-a152-8391caf6590d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f3cc5b4f-c43e-4a5a-9f94-654d0be55d3b",
      "position": 13,
      "properties": {
        "description": "This is a good time to commit our code and save our `Dessert` class and subclass to the Backpack. We will be adding to the classes throughout the unit as we learn more about designing classes and their components.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f3cc5b4f-c43e-4a5a-9f94-654d0be55d3b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "10f18409-a2b1-409d-a152-8391caf6590d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4daafa4f-e7d0-49b7-9e3a-3813057f72e0",
      "position": 14,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Play the music clip to cue committing their code and saving their `Dessert` class and subclass to the Backpack.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Using music to cue transitions helps create routines in the classroom. When students hear cues, they know it is time to transition to a specific activity. Emphasize to students what the music clip means, and be consistent with the use of the music clip to cue the activity.\n\nClick the blue play icon on the slide to play the music cue."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4daafa4f-e7d0-49b7-9e3a-3813057f72e0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "10f18409-a2b1-409d-a152-8391caf6590d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "90db396d-23cf-4712-b426-1867146d6291",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the concepts covered in this lesson.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Question of the Day.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Key Vocabulary",
        "name": "Show What You Know Week"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "90db396d-23cf-4712-b426-1867146d6291",
        "lesson_activity.key": "78b73655-b0e0-4b70-b8be-325122d4df16"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "24b0ed85-56d9-4376-93d6-4dc43069d0a5",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "---"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "24b0ed85-56d9-4376-93d6-4dc43069d0a5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "78b73655-b0e0-4b70-b8be-325122d4df16"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "800694a6-78ea-4d57-8663-55126e13e0d6",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "*Check For Understanding Question(s) and solutions can be found in each lesson on Code Studio. These questions can be used for an exit ticket.*",
        "name": "Assessment: Check for Understanding",
        "progression_name": "Check for Understanding"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "800694a6-78ea-4d57-8663-55126e13e0d6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "78b73655-b0e0-4b70-b8be-325122d4df16"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7ba2bc4e-9d9a-4612-92ed-976c8e38a0da",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *Imagine you’re designing the opening scene of a short animated story. It can be based on a favorite book, a memory, or something completely made up. What is one thing you would want your audience to notice or feel from this scene?\"*\n* *What kinds of visual or sound elements could help communicate that?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students explore how code can be used for creative expression. Encourage them to think like designers, identifying which visual and auditory elements might convey emotion, setting, or tone. This primes them to see The Theater as a flexible tool for storytelling, not just data display.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Have students share with a partner or write down a few ideas before sharing out. This sets the stage for thinking creatively about how to use the classes and methods in The Theater without tying the lesson to the data visualization project."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7ba2bc4e-9d9a-4612-92ed-976c8e38a0da",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4e6feedf-8fda-4c01-9723-b32096008e7b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4a74afe5-7b59-432f-948f-c2767204902d",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Introduction"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4a74afe5-7b59-432f-948f-c2767204902d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e139db1b-4cea-4320-8ec9-f8cf20f36526"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "cad45564-e486-4e06-b705-57330db69b14",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We have used packages like The Neighborhood and from the Java API to work with user input and files in our programs. In this unit, we will work with a package that contains classes that make up The Theater.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "cad45564-e486-4e06-b705-57330db69b14",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e139db1b-4cea-4320-8ec9-f8cf20f36526"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "74f60e52-fafe-48af-9cff-9d06c8d9a7e5",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 1 on Code Studio to predict the program's outcome, then run the program to compare their predictions to the actual outcome.",
        "progression_name": "Predict and Run: The Theater"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "74f60e52-fafe-48af-9cff-9d06c8d9a7e5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e139db1b-4cea-4320-8ec9-f8cf20f36526"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e1346f7f-35ec-4e70-8f73-b6759546e753",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What did you notice about the code in this program?*\n* *What do you wonder about the code in this program?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students notice that the program creates a `Scene` object and calls methods to draw shapes and images and play sounds. Students may wonder if they can extend the `Scene` class like they extended the `Painter` class or what types of programs they could create using The Theater."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e1346f7f-35ec-4e70-8f73-b6759546e753",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e139db1b-4cea-4320-8ec9-f8cf20f36526"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a9b295d0-a3e2-4b6a-98dd-11b7a7f665bb",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Show the video – Welcome to The Theater.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Investigating The Theater",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Videos are used throughout the curriculum to spark discussions, supplement key concepts with additional explanations and examples, and expose students to the various roles and backgrounds of individuals in computer science.\n\nWhile interacting with the video, turn on closed captioning so students can also read along as they watch.\n\nTo encourage active engagement and reflection, use one or more of the strategies discussed in the [**Guide to Curriculum Videos**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1FqIUpJg6MrgdtbFGLobSojOz0u1m5Jge1nMAjUqI5ZM/edit?usp=sharing)."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a9b295d0-a3e2-4b6a-98dd-11b7a7f665bb",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e139db1b-4cea-4320-8ec9-f8cf20f36526"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2fca14c2-4566-45d6-ac64-1d698c97c5e2",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Like The Neighborhood, The Theater consists of several classes that allow us to showcase our ideas and creativity. The main classes we'll be working with are the `Theater` and `Scene` classes.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2fca14c2-4566-45d6-ac64-1d698c97c5e2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e139db1b-4cea-4320-8ec9-f8cf20f36526"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5d58cb10-070d-4071-bde2-e5e87434f03b",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to introduce the Theater class.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "You don't need to go into too much detail about the `final` or `static` keywords for now. These are covered in more detail in an upcoming lesson."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5d58cb10-070d-4071-bde2-e5e87434f03b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e139db1b-4cea-4320-8ec9-f8cf20f36526"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "00fbaa54-3ff6-464c-a55a-d72f8d439e32",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Do This:** Introduce the `Scene` class:\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Default values for text, color, stroke, and instrument\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Instance variables for the font and colors\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Methods to get the width and height of The Theater, play sounds and notes, draw images and shapes, and change the font and colors\n\n**Group:** Place students in pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student a copy of the Investigating The Theater handout.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 2 on Code Studio to access the documentation for The Theater and complete the Investigating The Theater handout.",
        "progression_name": "Investigate and Modify: The Theater"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "00fbaa54-3ff6-464c-a55a-d72f8d439e32",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e139db1b-4cea-4320-8ec9-f8cf20f36526"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "20fd1e9f-e338-4f1c-8b00-3b36883dd907",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students share what they discovered from the modifications they made to the code and their responses on the Investigating The Theater handout.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Ask students what they noticed about the classes in the program, and have them share how this is similar and different to how they worked with the `Painter` class in The Neighborhood. You might also have students brainstorm how they might create additional `Scene` objects in a program and how they could work with them in a 1D array of `Scene` objects. For example:\n* *What are some other types of `Scene` objects you might create for a program?*\n* *If you created a 1D array of `Scene` objects, what are some things that you would then be able to do?*"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "20fd1e9f-e338-4f1c-8b00-3b36883dd907",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e139db1b-4cea-4320-8ec9-f8cf20f36526"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2f04ceeb-181f-431e-a785-14e02aa3831c",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Do This:** Click through the animated slides to introduce the methods in The Theater:\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> The `drawImage()` method\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> The methods to draw shapes\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> The `playSound()` and `playNote()` methods\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> The `pause()` method\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> The `Theater.playScenes()` method"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2f04ceeb-181f-431e-a785-14e02aa3831c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e139db1b-4cea-4320-8ec9-f8cf20f36526"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4bcd3aee-ed44-4ae2-9b4f-200c5c41ab42",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "The Theater allows you to create many types of visuals and animations, as well as play and manipulate sounds. Let's see what we can make in The Theater!",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Creating Drawings and Animations",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4bcd3aee-ed44-4ae2-9b4f-200c5c41ab42",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e139db1b-4cea-4320-8ec9-f8cf20f36526"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "610ff789-c404-4266-a844-5d27b91aff36",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 3 on Code Studio to complete Levels 3 through 5. Students complete choice levels to draw images, draw shapes, and play sounds.",
        "progression_name": "Practice: Creating Drawings and Animations",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Check for Understanding is an AP-style multiple choice question that can be used as a formative assessment to gauge understanding of 1D array algorithms.\n\nThe practice levels can be used as a formative assessment to gauge understanding of using API documentation and calling methods from existing classes."
          },
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Since these levels are focused on providing students opportunities for creative exploration with The Theater, they do not have validation."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "610ff789-c404-4266-a844-5d27b91aff36",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e139db1b-4cea-4320-8ec9-f8cf20f36526"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "34729337-ce96-4ae9-a80a-c650d383047a",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "There is a lot you can do with The Theater, and there are more capabilities that we have not yet explored. We'll start with the capabilities you explored today in this unit to create interesting visuals and animations.",
        "name": "Using The Theater",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "34729337-ce96-4ae9-a80a-c650d383047a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9fd6cd8c-818c-4f4d-80ca-0e2eb36cc1c0"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c904b2b2-033f-4b2a-825f-e8e595db7b52",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What are things you could make using The Theater?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students share ideas about visuals and animations they want to make using The Theater, such as creating a drawing of a favorite hobby or an animation to tell a personal story.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Hold That Thought strategy to allow students to write down their thoughts on paper first. Emphasize that they do not need to write complete sentences – they can write a few words, bullet points, draw a quick sketch, or anything else that will help them gather and recall their thoughts when it is time to share with the class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c904b2b2-033f-4b2a-825f-e8e595db7b52",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9fd6cd8c-818c-4f4d-80ca-0e2eb36cc1c0"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a3e1241a-2e5b-4315-bb8c-c462c66cba07",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the concepts covered in this lesson.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a3e1241a-2e5b-4315-bb8c-c462c66cba07",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9fd6cd8c-818c-4f4d-80ca-0e2eb36cc1c0"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "05eb904d-b3df-4f8d-b64d-77ec50ebba69",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "---"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "05eb904d-b3df-4f8d-b64d-77ec50ebba69",
