    {
      "key": "95e46f34-20fc-4c72-8feb-87a9c01f63d8",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "*Check For Understanding Question(s) and solutions can be found in each lesson on Code Studio. These questions can be used for an exit ticket.*",
        "name": "Assessment: Check for Understanding",
        "progression_name": "Check for Understanding"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "95e46f34-20fc-4c72-8feb-87a9c01f63d8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9fd6cd8c-818c-4f4d-80ca-0e2eb36cc1c0"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2899cb02-a1a7-4968-a942-e983fe43c6cd",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Sometimes the way information is represented and stored impacts the way we work with the data. Let's take a look at one scenario.",
        "name": "Finding Distances",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2899cb02-a1a7-4968-a942-e983fe43c6cd",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b0f02eeb-c787-4353-9a29-4d8dba8cdfe5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f5c9dff5-0b3e-4715-af84-3cdff49a9880",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the scenario.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *A principal wants to know the average distance each student lives from the school. If we use these negative values, we won't get an accurate result. How can we convert these negative values to positive values so we can get the average distance each student lives from the school?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students suggest solutions to convert the negative values to positive values, such as using an if statement to check if the value is negative and multiplying it by -1 to convert it to a positive value. Students might also suggest writing a separate method to convert numbers to a positive value and call it while traversing the 1D array to calculate the average.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Ask students to consider the efficiency or impacts of their proposed solutions. For example, if students suggest multiplying all negative values by `-1`, have students share ideas about how they would need to write the algorithm to ensure that positive values aren't converted to negative values."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f5c9dff5-0b3e-4715-af84-3cdff49a9880",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b0f02eeb-c787-4353-9a29-4d8dba8cdfe5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "481dada5-5ce8-4b7d-b3be-d2d0407f0450",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Introduction"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "481dada5-5ce8-4b7d-b3be-d2d0407f0450",
        "lesson_activity.key": "eea98b13-8bbc-4f90-bb5d-e70ad1a92e72"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "fcc181fe-b776-421d-b2ac-d7e6308be867",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We have explored several classes in the Java API, such as the `Scanner` class and the `Object` class. Today, we're going to take a look at another class that is available in the Java API.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "fcc181fe-b776-421d-b2ac-d7e6308be867",
        "lesson_activity.key": "eea98b13-8bbc-4f90-bb5d-e70ad1a92e72"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c3f23b20-b0a2-4664-98f4-59df21e2d09d",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 1 on Code Studio to predict the program's outcome, then run the program to compare their predictions to the actual outcome.",
        "progression_name": "Predict and Run: The Math Class"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c3f23b20-b0a2-4664-98f4-59df21e2d09d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "eea98b13-8bbc-4f90-bb5d-e70ad1a92e72"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "99a16211-a7af-435c-972b-8624dba026ba",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What did you notice about the code in this program?*\n* *What do you wonder about the code in this program?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students notice the methods in the `Math` class for square root, exponent, and absolute value. Students should also notice that the methods are called on the `Math` class instead of creating a `Math` object. Students may wonder what other methods are in the `Math` class and how they might use these in their programs."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "99a16211-a7af-435c-972b-8624dba026ba",
        "lesson_activity.key": "eea98b13-8bbc-4f90-bb5d-e70ad1a92e72"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f2a079f0-1be3-4931-89c1-abf106fa4f67",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Sometimes, we need to share a value across all objects that should not change. In these cases, we can use a static variable that is a constant.",
        "name": "Constants",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f2a079f0-1be3-4931-89c1-abf106fa4f67",
        "lesson_activity.key": "eea98b13-8bbc-4f90-bb5d-e70ad1a92e72"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4ea77de6-9d29-4d52-9cc7-d9f7379a2db5",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Show the video – *Constants*.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Videos are used throughout the curriculum to spark discussions, supplement key concepts with additional explanations and examples, and expose students to the various roles and backgrounds of individuals in computer science.\n\nWhile interacting with the video, turn on closed captioning so students can also read along as they watch.\n\nTo encourage active engagement and reflection, use one or more of the strategies discussed in the [**Guide to Curriculum Videos**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1FqIUpJg6MrgdtbFGLobSojOz0u1m5Jge1nMAjUqI5ZM/edit?usp=sharing)."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4ea77de6-9d29-4d52-9cc7-d9f7379a2db5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "eea98b13-8bbc-4f90-bb5d-e70ad1a92e72"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "489b9af5-f54e-454a-a3fc-ba7d48bba09d",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***constant***.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Where have you used constants before? How were they useful?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students share examples of constants they have seen or used before, such as pi in math class.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Retrieve-Pair-Share strategy to facilitate this discussion by directing students to write down their thoughts and ideas first, then pair up students to compare their answers and expand their notes. This allows time for individual processing and idea generation before sharing thoughts with others. Ask students to share the ideas they discussed with their partners as a class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "489b9af5-f54e-454a-a3fc-ba7d48bba09d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "eea98b13-8bbc-4f90-bb5d-e70ad1a92e72"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "35641538-9a2a-4be4-a6c6-1ab16e43ca7d",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the `Math` class.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce `Math.PI`."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "35641538-9a2a-4be4-a6c6-1ab16e43ca7d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "eea98b13-8bbc-4f90-bb5d-e70ad1a92e72"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "03656e71-c6be-449d-84a6-d8676445ab8e",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "The `Math` class has several methods and constants we can use to perform mathematical operations in our programs. To find out what we can do with the `Math` class, we just have to look at its documentation!",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Exploring the Math Class",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "03656e71-c6be-449d-84a6-d8676445ab8e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "eea98b13-8bbc-4f90-bb5d-e70ad1a92e72"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0d6b421d-3ad9-43ef-b712-9aeb227b573b",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Group:** Place students in pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student a copy of the The Math Class handout.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 2 on Code Studio to access the documentation for the Math class and complete The Math Class handout.",
        "progression_name": "Investigate and Modify: The Math Class"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0d6b421d-3ad9-43ef-b712-9aeb227b573b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "eea98b13-8bbc-4f90-bb5d-e70ad1a92e72"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "bf499ede-aaac-4711-8030-f541eb48c680",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students share what they discovered from the modifications they made to the code.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Have students share things that they found interesting about the `Math` class or any questions they might have."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "bf499ede-aaac-4711-8030-f541eb48c680",
        "lesson_activity.key": "eea98b13-8bbc-4f90-bb5d-e70ad1a92e72"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b5edcf65-b100-40ea-a9a0-a5b2e45d1c00",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Now that we have a better understanding of static methods, constants, and the `Math` class, we will focus on three of its methods. While you may have noticed that the `Math` class has many different methods, we will practice using methods to calculate absolute values, square roots, and exponents.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Using Math Class Methods",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b5edcf65-b100-40ea-a9a0-a5b2e45d1c00",
        "lesson_activity.key": "eea98b13-8bbc-4f90-bb5d-e70ad1a92e72"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "bcf4e129-f636-406c-b174-c081e454a294",
      "position": 13,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Do This:** Click through the animated slides to demonstrate the `Math` class methods:\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> `Math.abs(double a)` to calculate and return the absolute value of a `double` value\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> `Math.sqrt(double a)` to calculate and return the square root of a `double` value\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> `Math.pow(double a, double b)` to calculate and return the result of one `double` value raised to the power of the second `double` value",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "When calculating the square root of a negative number, Java returns `NaN`, which stands for \"Not a Number.\" Negative numbers do not have square roots (since they must be positive or zero), so Java will always return `NaN`."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "bcf4e129-f636-406c-b174-c081e454a294",
        "lesson_activity.key": "eea98b13-8bbc-4f90-bb5d-e70ad1a92e72"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6850332e-a8b9-4f1a-a116-0f2f0f181f70",
      "position": 14,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Now that we’re familiar with how each of these methods works, let’s practice using them!",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6850332e-a8b9-4f1a-a116-0f2f0f181f70",
        "lesson_activity.key": "eea98b13-8bbc-4f90-bb5d-e70ad1a92e72"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "132eafb0-dab6-45b5-817e-c500e83d42e9",
      "position": 15,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 3 on Code Studio to complete Levels 3 through 7. Students complete a Check for Understanding on Level 3, then continue to Level 4 to complete a choice level to create and use a constant. Students then complete choice levels on Levels 5 through 7 to practice using methods in the `Math` class.",
        "progression_name": "Practice: The Math Class",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "It is okay if students do not finish all of the levels. All levels involve using the `Math` class methods highlighted in this lesson while also allowing students to practice with content from previous lessons.\n\nStudents will have access to the Java Quick Reference on the AP Exam, which includes the `Math` class methods from this lesson."
          },
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Check for Understanding is an AP-style multiple choice question that can be used as a formative assessment to gauge understanding of evaluating expressions using methods in the `Math` class.\n\nThe practice levels can be used as a formative assessment to gauge understanding of creating and using constants and calling methods in the `Math` class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "132eafb0-dab6-45b5-817e-c500e83d42e9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "eea98b13-8bbc-4f90-bb5d-e70ad1a92e72"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6bcd000d-445d-400e-a351-53428232c5fc",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student a copy of the Math Class Graphic Organizer handout.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to complete the Math Class Graphic Organizer handout.",
        "name": "Math Class Graphic Organizer",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "You can also have students work with a partner to complete their graphic organizer. If time permits, have students share what they wrote on their graphic organizer with a neighbor or as a class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6bcd000d-445d-400e-a351-53428232c5fc",
        "lesson_activity.key": "34ef783a-58bd-402b-afa0-4e7cadae32a8"
      }
    },
