      "key": "288438e7-6fd8-4cae-94bb-caabc849f8b1",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "*Check For Understanding Question(s) and solutions can be found in each lesson on Code Studio. These questions can be used for an exit ticket.*",
        "name": "Assessment: Check for Understanding",
        "progression_name": "Check for Understanding"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "288438e7-6fd8-4cae-94bb-caabc849f8b1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a5398639-2c8f-43a3-9a80-b9150897e37b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "86044b69-432f-4153-9301-86e85d97091e",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "You've probably used a smart assistant before. These use natural language processing techniques to break up the things you say and get the meaning of the individual words in your statement or question.",
        "name": "Smart Assistants",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "86044b69-432f-4153-9301-86e85d97091e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e6f4d4fe-689c-424e-a380-21c169257789"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a7e4ae6a-15c1-4f88-a590-d77f088b37e0",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *When we ask Siri questions, it performs a specific task or gives a response based on our question or statement. But how does it know what task to perform or how to respond?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students suggest that it identifies keywords in the question or statement to determine what action to perform or how it should respond. For example, if it finds the word \"weather\", then it knows it needs to respond with weather information.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Retrieve-Pair-Share strategy to facilitate this discussion by directing students to write down their thoughts and ideas first, then pair up students to compare their answers and expand their notes. This allows time for individual processing and idea generation before sharing thoughts with others. Ask students to share the ideas they discussed with their partners as a class.\n\nYou can also ask students additional guiding questions to help them realize that smart assistants are identifying keywords and how they might do this. For example:\n* *If you tell Siri to send a message to your friend, how does it know that you want to send a message? How does it know who to send it to? What about what the message itself should be?*\n* *How do you think it breaks up your question or statement to find these pieces?*"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a7e4ae6a-15c1-4f88-a590-d77f088b37e0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e6f4d4fe-689c-424e-a380-21c169257789"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "47652f64-38da-4595-8849-3cf37a0f6321",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Introduction"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "47652f64-38da-4595-8849-3cf37a0f6321",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c525539d-0d23-433f-9ea3-187aa3a7b157"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d4ed7ee7-229d-4621-a61d-0d5810468700",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We previously learned about the `String` class and some of its methods we can use to find the location of specific characters in a `String` object or its length. Today, we'll learn about another useful method in the `String` class that allows us to retrieve a portion of a `String`.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d4ed7ee7-229d-4621-a61d-0d5810468700",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c525539d-0d23-433f-9ea3-187aa3a7b157"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e2308ae9-698f-4390-b989-a56f33e02b9b",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 1 on Code Studio to predict the program's outcome, then run the program to compare their predictions to the actual outcome.",
        "progression_name": "Predict and Run: The substring() Method"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e2308ae9-698f-4390-b989-a56f33e02b9b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c525539d-0d23-433f-9ea3-187aa3a7b157"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7a477d68-7696-4d4e-8f25-7d5db29d729d",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What did you notice about the code in this program?*\n* *What do you wonder about the code in this program?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students notice that there are two versions of the `substring()` method. They realize that the two-parameter version of the `substring()` method returns the characters between the specified index values and that the one-parameter version returns the characters starting at the specified index values to the end of the `String`."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7a477d68-7696-4d4e-8f25-7d5db29d729d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c525539d-0d23-433f-9ea3-187aa3a7b157"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8b7a5415-811d-42b2-9d8e-2cd07691fe46",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "When we use the `substring()` method, we can get the characters between a starting and ending index in a `String` object or from a starting index to the end of the `String` object.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "The substring() Method",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8b7a5415-811d-42b2-9d8e-2cd07691fe46",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c525539d-0d23-433f-9ea3-187aa3a7b157"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f87f9b27-0af5-4211-a4de-84d2a8872239",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 2 on Code Studio complete Levels 2, 3, and 4. Students investigate the program, make changes to the program as prompted, and observe the results.",
        "progression_name": "Investigate and Modify: The substring() Method"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f87f9b27-0af5-4211-a4de-84d2a8872239",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c525539d-0d23-433f-9ea3-187aa3a7b157"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "db54e788-91e5-47d8-92b6-3b9ae81729c1",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students share what they discovered from the modifications they made to the code.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to demonstrate the one parameter `substring()` method.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to demonstrate the two parameter `substring()` method.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to demonstrate using the `substring()` method to obtain a single element in a `String`.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to demonstrate that `String` objects are immutable and that `String` methods do not change the `String` object."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "db54e788-91e5-47d8-92b6-3b9ae81729c1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c525539d-0d23-433f-9ea3-187aa3a7b157"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "412d5c82-bafa-4989-80a5-5756b761051e",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 5 on Code Studio to complete Levels 5 through 8. Students complete a Check for Understanding on Level 5, then continue to Level 6 to complete a choice level on Levels 6 and 7 to practice using the `substring()` method to retrieve characters between a starting and ending index and from a starting index to the end of a `String` object. On Level 8, students complete a choice level to use the `indexOf()` and `substring()` methods.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Using the substring() Method",
        "progression_name": "Practice: The substring() Method",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Check for Understanding is an AP-style multiple choice question that can be used as a formative assessment to gauge understanding of using the `substring()` method.\n\nThe practice level can be used as a formative assessment to gauge understanding of using the `substring()` and `indexOf()` methods."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "412d5c82-bafa-4989-80a5-5756b761051e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c525539d-0d23-433f-9ea3-187aa3a7b157"
      }
