      }
    },
    {
      "key": "25d8cec6-fb5d-45e4-96f2-1526ec168118",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "The `compareTo()` method is useful for when we need to sort a list of `String` objects in lexicographical order. In natural language processing programs and devices, software engineers often need to organize text to make it easier to work with in their programs.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Comparing String Objects",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "25d8cec6-fb5d-45e4-96f2-1526ec168118",
        "lesson_activity.key": "028db449-d47b-488a-9d95-455d22b4e976"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c16bf09a-6185-4ad3-96da-652961ea153c",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to demonstrate the `compareTo()` method.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students respond to the self-check question, then click through the animated slide to display and discuss the solution.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 5 on Code Studio to complete Levels 5, 6, and 7. Students complete a Check for Understanding, then continue to Level 6 to complete a choice level to practice using the `compareTo()` method. On Level 7, students complete a choice level to practice using the methods in the String class.",
